<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Ends Inspection of Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIZHOU, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng has urged people
in southwest China's Guizhou Province to build up their confidence
in developing local economy and strive for success by relying
on their own efforts.
</P>
<P>
The premier made an inspection tour of the poverty-stricken
province from July 18 to 20, accompanied by the secretary of the
provincial committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the
governor of the province.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng visited rural households, a revolutionary educational
base and factories. He sent corcial regards to local people on
behalf of President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed the achievements the province has made over recent
years in various sectors and noted that the gaps are still
existing between Guizhou and other provinces.
</P>
<P>
The premier urged the provincial authorities to give top
priority to developing agriculture and introduce farming
technologies which suit local conditions.
</P>
<P>
Citing the development of communications as the key to local
economic development, he said both the central government and
local authorities will work jointly to complete the construction
of some major highways and railway lines in Guizhou in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
Attention should also be paid to exploiting tourism resources
in the province, for it has numerous natural scenic spots, he
added.
</P>
<P>
On his inspection tour, Li attached great importance to
poverty-relief work. He noted that the task is arduous, for there
are still six million people in the province who are in want and
need, most of them are concentrated in the mountainous and outlying
ethnic-minority areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called on local authorities to make hard and
conscientious efforts and take concrete steps to eliminate poverty
and give due consideration to the development of cultural,
educational and scientific undertakings in the process.
</P>
<P>
The premier also showed kind attention to flood victims in
Guizhou and urged local authorities to take prompt and special
measures to help them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
