<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Mediator Announces Progress on W.Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. envoy James Baker today
announced positive results in talks between Morocco and its
Western Sahara foes, the Polisario Front.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to say that we have reached agreement with
respect to the bridging proposals that we submitted in Lisbon last
month," Baker, a former U.S. Secretary of State, told reporters
here after one-and-a-half-day of talks.
</P>
<P>
The secret proposals aim at breaking a long-standing deadlock
to resolve a dispute between Morocco and the Algerian-backed
Polisario, which wants to be an independent state, on the question
of who would be allowed to vote in a referendum on the future of
the desert region.
</P>
<P>
Morocco and Polisario fought a 16-year war over the Western
Sahara after Spain pulled out in 1976 and four-fifths of the
region is under Moroccan control.
</P>
<P>
Baker, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's mediator, said he
was encouraged by the deal on identification, which he called a
very difficult issue.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. secretary of state, who will report to the
U.N. Security Council in New York on Monday, said the two sides,
along with observers, Algeria and Mauritania, had also agreed to
cooperate on the issue of refugees.
</P>
<P>
But he said the agreement did not necessarily mean a
breakthrough in the long-standing dispute.
</P>
<P>
"Both parties have agreed to abide by the provisions of that
compromise proposal and if we are able -- if, that's a big if --
to reach agreement with respect to all of these other issues which
are in dispute... then we may have a chance to move this process
forward," Baker said.
</P>
<P>
Baker said a third round of talks would be held in late August
for further discussion of the dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
