<HEADLINE> Most of World AIDS Cases in Sub-Saharan Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- AIDS cases in sub-Saharan Africa
account for at least 75 percent of all the reported ones in the
world, said the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
The Zambia News Agency today quoted WHO as saying that since
the discovery of the first case of AIDS in the early 1980s, there
have been approximately 4.5 million cases in the region which
represents 75 percent of the world estimate of 6 million cases.
</P>
<P>
It said in the region a lot of people still have
misconceptions about the disease and its mode of transmission
although the great majority of them have heard of AIDS/HIV.
</P>
<P>
In the sub-Saharan Africa sexual contact has been identified
as the major mode of transmission and this has been aggravated by
the wide practice of men having multiple sex partners.
</P>
<P>
The condom is still the second major method to prevent the
spread of AIDS/HIV in the region, according to WHO.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia and Zimbabwe, as a result of intensive social
marketing of the condom, 70 percent of men use condoms for the
double purpose of AIDS/HIV and unwanted pregnancy prevention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
