<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adams Condemns Report of IRA Ceasefire Time Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams
today condemned media reports that a new truce by his Irish
Republican Army(IRA) allies might last only four months, saying
the British secret services sought to undermine peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is the political wing of the Irish Republican Army,
an outlawed guerrilla group which has launched military campaign
to end the British rule of Northern Ireland since 1968.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Tribune, published in Dublin, reported that the IRA
leadership had told its members that the ceasefire would last four
months and would be renewed only if the province's peace process
was seen to produce political benefits for Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
IRA announced a ceasefire on Saturday which took effect at
midday today. The truce, demanded by the government, would allow
Sinn Fein to gain a place in the all-party peace talks on the
future of the divided province.
</P>
<P>
Adams also called on Unionists politicians to lay aside their
doubts and join in negotiations to settle years of communal
division.
</P>
<P>
Politicians for the province's Protestant majority are deeply
suspicious of IRA's motives. They are infuriated that the truce
paves the way for Sinn Fein to enter settlement talks without any
guerrilla arms being handed over.
</P>
<P>
Unionist parties are threatening to walk out of current
multi-party talks, which exclude Sinn Fein, in protest at what
they say are weak Anglo-Irish plans for achieving a surrender of
guerrilla arms.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, head of the powerful Ulster Unionist Party, is
due to have hold talks with Prime Minister Tony Blair in London on
Monday to urge him to toughen demands for IRA disarmament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
