<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Reopen Crossing Leading to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Defense Minister Mohsen
Dalloul reiterated today his government's determination to reopen
a crossing leading to an Israeli-occupied enclave in order to
"alleviate sufferings of residents" in the southern border
area.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese authorities have announced that the crossing
will be ready for passage for the first time in 11 years on
August 1, the Lebanese Army Day.
</P>
<P>
Dalloul was quoted by the state-run Lebanese National News
Agency as saying that the government "will not accept any of
Israeli conditions to open the Kfar Falous crossing" between the
south Lebanese port city of Saida and the occupied town of
Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Council of Ministers' decision on the
opening was aimed at "alleviating sufferings of residents in
Jezzine and facilitating the communication" from the border
strip to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz stressed today that it is an
obligation of the state to open the Kfar Falous crossing in
order to dismantle the blockade imposed by Israel around
Jezzine, 75 kilometers southeast of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the Beirut Airport upon his departure
for Austria, the foreign minister underlined that "the
government will do everything it can to support sons of Jezzine
in their perseverance in their area, in their homes and on their
land."
</P>
<P>
Jezzine, a beleaguered city of 35,000, just out from the
northern tip of the occupied border strip and is often
"inspected" by patrols of the 2,500-strong South Lebanon Army
(SLA) militia, which polices the enclave in concert with
1,000-strong Israeli occupation forces.
</P>
<P>
Muslim guerrillas of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of
God, mounted two bombing attacks on SLA patrols on the southern
outskirts of the mainly Christian-populated town last month,
killing two militiamen and two civilians.
</P>
<P>
The rare assaults in the area provoked the city's residents
to stage protest demonstrations and demand Lebanese army
protections, prompting the government to declare it would reopen
the Kfar Kalous crossing, which has been closed since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Antoine Lahd, the Israeli-appointed commander of the SLA
militia, declared Thursday his agreement to let the crossing be
reopened.
</P>
<P>
The retired Lebanese army general's move came days after his
militiamen shelled Lebanese army units who had spent two weeks
removing mines and barricades on the road leading to Kfar
Falous.
</P>
<P>
Lahd said he would clear the sector of road under SLA control
but warned that he would immediately block the crossing and
bombard the area "without any prior warning" if the crossing was
used by resistance guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that the Lebanese army not be deployed near Kfar
Falous, leaving the crossing and its vicinities as part of the
existing no-man's land between the occupied zone and the rest of
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
