<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maize Surplus Forecast in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique, which achieved maize
self-sufficiency for the first time after decades of domestic
production shortfalls is likely to have a surplus of close to
54,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) early warning
unit today said surplus was forecast in the major maize growing
northern provinces of Niassa, Cabo Delgado, Nampula and Zambezia.
</P>
<P>
''This reflects the significantly improved production
prospects brought about by increased plantings and better yields
helped by good rains and improved supply of seed and farming
tools,'' said the unit.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since independence in 1975, Mozambique
seems to have notched a rare success story in efforts to prop up
agricultural recovery, with locally produced maize expected to
reach an all-time high of 1.043 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 10 percent higher than last year's record
harvest of 947,000 tons, the unit said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
