<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRSP in Northern Ireland Rejects IRA Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Socialist
Party (IRSP) today rejected a ceasefire proposed at the weekend by
the IRA, saying the truce would not help end British "occupation"
in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the IRSP said that the truce, which will allow
the IRA's political wing Sinn Fein to participate in the peace
talks, would not help get Ireland united.
</P>
<P>
The IRSP is the political wing of a small but deadly
anti-British guerrilla group in Northern Ireland, the Irish
National Liberation Army (INLA), which broke away from the IRA in
1976.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Army (IRA), which has launched a military
campaign over the past 28 years to end the British rule of
Northern Ireland, called a ceasefire Saturday which took effect on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"It is our view that the so-called peace process is little
more than a thinly veiled attempt at pacifying Nationalist demands
while neutralizing Republican resistance to the British occupation
of Ireland," the IRSP said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The INLA never declared a ceasefire in its war against
Britain. It claimed responsibility for several shooting attacks on
Northern Ireland security personnel during riots this month over
annually held Protestant Orange Order parades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
