<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Solidarity Conference Opens in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Conference of Arab Parties and
Non-governmental Organizations in Support of Arab Solidarity
opened here today in a bid to close Arab ranks.
</P>
<P>
At the outset of the two-day conference, Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak stressed that Egypt seeks together with other
Arab countries to restore Arab solidarity and boost cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt seeks to activate the role played by the Arab League
(AL) and its specialized organizations to become more capable of
facing up to new changes and expressing Arab aspirations for a
new era of cooperation within the framework of a just and overall
peace," he said in a speech read out on his behalf at the
inaugural session.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the conference, AL Secretary General Esmat-Abdul
Meguid underlined that the issue of Arab solidarity has been
given top priority at present.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, read out by the league's assistant secretary
general, Ahmed Bin Helmi, Meguid stressed the importance of
building Arab solidarity on "clear bases and joint interests."
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League made long strides for clearing Arab
atmospheres and ironing out differences," he said, adding that the
Cairo Arab Summit held in June last year opened a new stage for
joint actions.
</P>
<P>
He pinpointed the crying challenges facing the Arab states at
present as the deadlock in the Mideast peace process due to the
Israeli government's non-abidance by the peace principles and
intransigence on its settlement policy in the occupied Arab
territories as well as its attempts to Judaize Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of more than 50 parties and non-governmental
organizations attending the conference will discuss a number of
issues such as the Mideast peace process, economic integration,
the normalization of ties among some countries, and sanctions
imposed on some Arab states such as Iraq and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The conference, organized by the Egyptian Committee for
Solidarity with Afro-Asian Peoples, will release Tuesday a
statement including its recommendations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
