<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM's New Chief: We'll Do A Quick Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The new chief of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) Richard Butler said today that he and his
colleagues will complete their mission of disarming Iraq "as soon
as possible."
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here, Butler, a former Australian
ambassador to the U.N., also said that his commission will not be
influenced by any government.
</P>
<P>
He said "In my definite view, that time (six years of getting
rid of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction) has been too long and
we must try to find a way to complete the job" because "the time
has come," said the new chief.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-imposed sanctions on Iraq since 1990 will not be
lifted before the UNSCOM verifies that Iraq has destroyed all its
weapons of mass destruction, including chemical and nuclear
weapons and ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here this morning on his first visit to Iraq
after he replaced Rolf Ekues as executive chairman of the UNSCOM
on July 1.
</P>
<P>
He said he will endeavor to seek a solution of the current
crisis between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
His predecessor complained of non-cooperation from Iraq, while
Baghdad rejected the charge, described Ekues as a stooge of the
United States and held him responsible for the maintenance of the
international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution a month ago
threatening Iraq with further international sanctions within four
months should it fail to cooperate with the U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Butler also promised to be objective and independent in his
mission, adding he viewed his job as a "scientific and technical
one and the whole mark should be objectivity."
</P>
<P>
"I will not make political statements here or any where else,"
said Butler, adding that UNSCOM is responsible for giving the
Security Council a "credible" report on the process of disarming
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he is under any pressure from some Security Council
members, he told reporters that no government has given him any
instructions and vowed that either he or the UNSCOM will work
independently.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day stay, Butler is scheduled to meet Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz and other U.N. officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Optimistic About Trade in 2nd Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is cautiously
optimistic about the country's trade performance in the second
half of this year, as the turnaround in the global electronics
demand has begun and is likely to continue in the coming months,
the Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
It noted that non-oil domestic exports expanded by 4.4 percent
in the second quarter after contracting by 4.1 percent in the
first quarter. For the first half of 1997, the growth was 0.2
percent. Both electronics and non-electronics exports did well in
the second quarter, it said.
</P>
<P>
Electronics exports, which account for about 70 percent of
Singapore's non-oil domestic exports, rose by 4.2 percent in the
second quarter, with the major electronics exports, such as disk
drives, integrated circuits and personal computers registering
double digit growth rates, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
Given the better performance in the second quarter, the TDB
said that the outlook for the second half of 1997 "is one of
cautious optimism", as the recovery in the global electronics
demand is expected to continue in the upcoming months.
</P>
<P>
However, competition in the industry is likely to intensify,
which would exert downward pressure on prices of key electronic
products, resulting in the squeeze on profit margins, the TDB
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
