<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taylor Leads in Liberia's Preliminary Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 21 (Xinhua)- Preliminary votes from Liberia's
presidential elections released by the Independent Elections
Commission (IEC) in Monrovia today showed that Charles Taylor
from the National Patriotic Party (NPP) is in a comfortable lead
with a little over 66 percent votes.
</P>
<P>
According to Liberia radio monitored in the neighboring Sierra
Leone, it is now certain that Liberia's next president will be
Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Political observers said the election of Taylor will mean
there would not be a runoff with the other front-runner for the
presidency, Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, leader of the Unity Party.
</P>
<P>
The official result, said the radio, will not be known until
Tuesday or early Wednesday but there is little possibility that
today's election predictions will change.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the radio, Taylor said, "I believe in god
and he has always been my protector". He described the civil
crisis in Liberia in which he played a major part during the past
seven years as "the making of god to punish the Liberian people
for their sins. "
</P>
<P>
"I am prepared to lead Liberia and its people to higher
heights as my faith is always with god," he added.
</P>
<P>
Liberian officials in the election office said the
presidential winner will be sworn in six days from now at
programs marking the 150 years of the countrys' independence.
</P>
<P>
The election is regarded as the first genuine multi-party vote
in the country for at least some 100 years. For most of the
time, Liberian politicians have been dominated up to a proportion
of 19 to 5 by the only party in the country the whig.
</P>
<P>
During the reign of former President Samuel Doe, there was a
multi-party election, the result of which was not made public due
to charges of fraud.
</P>
<P>
The election in Liberia was watched with keen interest by
political leaders in the sub-region especially the junta regime
in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"A threat to peace in Liberia or in Sierra Leone can
destabilize either of these countries", a political observer here
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
