<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Supreme Leader: US Could not Hurt Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Supreme leader Ali
Khamenei said here today that the United States could not hurt
Iran because attacking Iran would make Iran more united and not
attacking Iran would make Iran stronger.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spiritual leader made the remarks while meeting
Jathliq Aram Keshishian, spiritual leader of the 4 million
Armenian Orthodox Christians living outside their homeland, the
state-run Tehran Radio reported. Keshishian arrived in Iran last
week.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that the worst the United States could ever do
was to attack Iran.
</P>
<P>
"If they don't attack us, they lose, because we get stronger
every day. And if they do attack, they still lose, because our
nation will unite under an attack and we will win more support
around the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that economic embargo was not an alternative for
Washington because the U.S. would stand the chance of losing its
allies.
</P>
<P>
"If it imposes economic sanctions on us, it would still be
against its interests, because our domestic activities would
increase and the U.S. would lose its allies, and may even lead to
manifestation of the internal contradiction in the American
regime," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei called the U.S. "the ultimate world tyrant" and held
the U.S. responsible for all the oppression in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Wherever there is evil and oppression, wherever there is
imposed war against nations, wherever there is repression of the
righteous struggle of the nations, you can see U.S. involvement
there," he said.
</P>
<P>
The statement by Khamenei is regarded by observers here as the
harshest attack on the United States since the presidential
election on May 23 in which moderate Mohammad Khatami won a
landslide victory by defeating Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar
Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the U.S. broke diplomatic ties on April 7, 1980, four
months after the seizure of the U.S. embassy in Tehran, the
capital of Iran, and taking of 62 U.S. hostages by radical
Islamic students.
</P>
<P>
Since then, relations between Iran and the United States have
remained hostile as Iran has opposed the U.S. efforts to broker
peace between Arabs and Israel in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The United States has accused Iran of backing anti-Israeli
forces in southern Lebanon and of backing anti-Arafat forces in
the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
However, Washington has changed its hostile tone toward Tehran
after the election of President-elect Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani has
reiterated that the U.S. should show its desire for improving
ties with Iran by releasing Iran's assets frozen after the
hostage crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
