<HEADLINE> Myanmar FM to Attend ASEAN Admission Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Foreign Minister U Ohn Gyaw
left here today for Malaysia to attend a ceremony to admit the
country along with Laos into the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) and the grouping's 30th Annual Ministerial Meeting
this week, the state-run Radio Myanmar and TV Myanmar reported
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar became observer of the ASEAN in July 1996 at the 29th
Annual ASEAN Ministerial Meeting held in Jakarta after acceding to
the Treaty of Amity and Cooperation in Southeast Asia at the July
1995 Brunei Meeting of ASEAN Foreign Ministers.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN had planned to admit Myanmar, Laos and Cambodia
simultaneously at the 30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM) this
week, expanding its membership to 10 nations.
</P>
<P>
But the plan was disrupted by factional fighting between the
forces of
Cambodian Co-Prime Ministers Hun Sen and Norodom Ranariddh on July
5 and
6. At a special foreign ministers meeting earlier this month, the
ASEAN
decided to postpone admitting Cambodia because of the fighting,
which
resulted in the ouster of First Prime Minister Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN currently groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
