<HEADLINE> Four Killed in Plane Crash in Southwest Missouri </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- All the four people aboard a
twin-engine aircraft were killed when the plane crashed into a
field and burst into flames Sunday afternoon near Springfield,
southwest Missouri, the Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Beechcraft Duke left Springfield for the Spirit of St.
Louis Airport near Chesterfield. But after it had flown about 25
kilometers, the pilot told controllers there were problems with
the left engine and said he was going to make an emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed into the bank of a dry pond in a pasture
about 3.5 kilometers outside Springfield.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Aviation Administration and the National
Transportation Safety Board were to investigate the cause of the
crash.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rescue divers on Sunday found the body of a seventh
person killed when two small planes collided above Lake Michigan
near Chicago.
</P>
<P>
The single-engine planes collided about 100 yards from shore
Saturday evening, killing five women and two men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
