<HEADLINE> China's Shanghai Reforms Rural Credit Cooperatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China's major economic and
financial center, Shanghai, has launched an effort to standardize
its rural credit cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
The first reformed and standardized rural credit cooperative,
the Shiwan Rural Credit Cooperative in the Pudong New Area, was
officially established last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Shanghai has a total of 227 rural credit
cooperatives, which were set up in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
As part of a program to reform its banking sector, China is
turning its urban credit cooperatives to cooperative banks. In the
countryside, efforts are being focused on standardizing the rural
credit cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
A Shanghai banking official said that after all the rural
credit cooperatives are standardized, Shanghai will begin to
establish rural cooperative banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
