<HEADLINE> ASEAN Suspends Help to Cambodia: Alatas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) has temporarily stopped offering help to Cambodia
because Hun Sen, the second prime minister of the country, had
rejected the offer, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said
today.
</P>
<P>
Alatas made the remarks when briefing a press conference on his
recent separate meetings with Cambodian King Sihanouk in Beijing,
Prince Ranariddh in Bangkok and Hun Sen in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
"The first thing we asked when we met them was whether they
wanted ASEAN to help them resolve the conflict," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Sihanouk and his son, Ranariddh, responded
positively to the offer, but Hun Sen rejected it.
</P>
<P>
"We must respect the involving parties' decisions. If Hun Sen
does not want ASEAN to assist, we will stop," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
However, Alatas said, ASEAN's decision to accept Cambodia as a
full member of the seven-member organization was still valid, but
the timetable would be postponed.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia still enjoyed the observer status in the group and
therefore could participate in ASEAN's upcoming ministerial
meeting as an observer, Alatas explained.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said he would report to the meeting, to be
held in Malaysia on July 23, the results of his talks with
Cambodian leaders.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
