<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preparations For World Bank/IMF Annual Meetings Go Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for the 1997 World
Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) annual meetings have
gone smoothly into the final stage, the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority announced today.
</P>
<P>
The annual meetings, jointly of the Boards of Governors of the
World Bank and the IMF, are scheduled to be held between
September 23 and 25 this year in Hong Kong, China.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing here today, James Lau, executive director
who oversees external affairs in the HKMA, said that the annual
meetings would attract some 14,000 participants from 180 countries
and regions all over the world. They will meet at the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center (HKCEC) and its newly-built
Extension, the venue of the handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"As the first major international event in Hong Kong after the
handover on July 1, 1997, the annual meetings will turn out to be
the focus of the world," said Lau, who chairs an organizing
committee responsible for coordination and planning of the local
logistical arrangements for the meetings.
</P>
<P>
The assembly will attract over 300 finance ministers and
central bank governors, around 4,000 government officials from 181
members of the World Bank and the IMF. In addition, 5,000 private
sector bankers and senior representatives from relevant
organizations will be present, as well as 2,000 local and overseas
journalists.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 Hong Kong Special Administrative Government staff
will join forces with 700 in-coming World Bank and IMF staff to
take care of detailed arrangements for "the most prestigious
annual event in the international financial community."
</P>
<P>
Both founded in 1945, the World Bank and the IMF hold their
annual meetings once every three years outside their headquarters
in Washington, DC, USA.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank aims to promote economic development, improve
the quality of life and provide loans for developing countries,
while the IMF's objectives are to promote international monetary
cooperation, facilitate expansion of international trade and
promote exchange rate stability.
</P>
<P>
The staging of the event this year in Hong Kong shows that the
World Bank and the IMF have both cast their strong vote of
confidence in the ongoing stability and prosperity of Hong Kong
after July 1, 1997, and in Hong Kong's continuing success as a
leading international financial center, according to the HKMA
official.
</P>
<P>
Lau said that the annual meetings would enhance Hong Kong's
status as an international financial center and bring substantial
economic benefits to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A variety of local working groups have been set up to arrange
venue facilities, communications system, hotel accommodations,
transportation, security, airport reception, registration, social
events and cultural programs.
</P>
<P>
Lau said the organizing committee has coordinated with a
preparatory team led by the Ministry of Finance and joined by such
agencies as the People's Bank of China and the State Council's
Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office.
</P>
<P>
An integral part of annual meetings is the program of seminars,
which will be held in the week before. This year's focus is on
Asia and the World: Capital, Competitiveness, and Community.
</P>
<P>
Lau said that about 3,000 major meetings, seminars, keynote
sessions and social events would be staged during the ten-day
period starting on September 16.
</P>
<P>
At the venue -- the HKCEC and its Extension, over 900 temporary
 offices will be set up, in addition to seven convention and
exhibition halls, two theaters and 56 meeting rooms. Advanced
technologies will be used, such as the bar-code system, which uses
 computers to spot forged or stolen badges so as to tighten
security.
</P>
<P>
According to the HKMA official, the expenditure for the event
would be well controlled within the budget of 485 million HK
dollars (62.5 million US dollars). The organizing committee has
secured 70 million HK dollars (nine million US dollars) of
sponsorship.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taylor Far Ahead in Liberian Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Charles Taylor, Liberia's
presidential candidate has won nearly 66 percent of the 219,754
votes counted so far in Saturday's election, according to the
Independent Elections Commission (IECOM) today.
</P>
<P>
A mid-day summary sheet of the poll counting faxed here from
IECOM in the capital Monrovia shows that the former warlord who
is running on the platform of the National Patriotic Party, has
got 144,981 of the 219,754 casts counted so far, accounting for
65.974 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
His closest rival, Unity Party's woman candidate, Ellen
Johnson-Sirleaf, received 34,914 votes, or 15.887 percent,
ranking the second.
</P>
<P>
In the third place is another major former warlord Alhaji
Kromah of the All Liberian Coalition Party, with only 9,448
votes, or 4.299 percent of the total, in hand.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 80 percent of more than 710,000 registered voters
participated in Saturday's election, the first democratic
election in 12 years which is expected to bring final peace to
the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
The 219,754 votes is from 684 of the total 1900 polling
stations countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Poll counting is still going on at the press time and the
final results are expected on Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
