<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Irish Republican Army's new cease-fire has officially
begun, bringing a cautious sense of relief to Catholics and
Protestants in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
-- Preliminary results from Liberia's presidential election on
Saturday placed Charles Taylor, the warlord who started the civil
war in Liberia in 1989 as the leader in the race.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The imminent expansion of NATO and the European Union toward
the east portends a shift in the continent's center of gravity
that is prompting a dramatic reassessment of Germany's strategic
interests.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich said Sunday night that he is
confident the vast majority of House Republicans support him
despite an aborted attempt to oust him and that only a handful of
the dissidents who plotted against him really wanted to remove
him.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Vietnam reported high voter turnout and no violence in
nationwide elections for its 450-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
-- Bosnian Serbaradzic allies accusing her of aiding the hunt
for war-crimes suspects. 
</P>
