<HEADLINE> Canada's Retail Sales Up in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Canada's retail sales continued a
steady trend of growth, advancing 0.5 percent to 14 billion U.S.
dollars in May, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
May's retail sales were 7.6 percent higher compared with the same
month a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
"Many consumers appeared to be parking a new car in the driveway of
their newly furnished homes," the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
The purchase of big-ticket items drove up retail sales in May, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
In May, sales by motor and recreational vehicle dealers were up 2.2
percent and furniture stores up 2.1 percent, which were the major
contributors to the month's growth.
</P>
<P>
"Continued low interest rates made the costs of financing purchases
attractive," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, improving sales by furniture stores may, in part, have
been spurred by the strong housing market, it added. 
</P>
