<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Let Market Determine Its Currency Value: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's foreign exchange
policy is to let the market forces determine the value of the
ringgit (local currency) based on the country's economic
fundamentals, Parliamentary Secretary of the Finance Ministry
Shafie Mohd Salleh said today.
</P>
<P>
He told the House of Representatives here today that the
Central Bank will only intervene in the foreign exchange market
when the ringgit depreciated drastically owing to intense currency
speculation.
</P>
<P>
The official said the government would ensure the central
bank's intervention would not be drastic because what was
happening now was only a temporary phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian currency's value began to depreciate when fixed
deposit fund managers recently involved in speculation of various
currencies in the region including the ringgit, he said during the
Question Time, according to the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The official said that in a country like Malaysia which is
practicing open economy, the fluctuation of the ringgit was not
only influenced by the local economic fundamentals but also
developments in the regional and worldwide foreign exchange
markets.
</P>
<P>
Shafie said the currency depreciation in the region did not
involve the ringgit alone but also the Philippines' peso,
Thailand's baht and Indonesia's rupiah as well as the Singapore
dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Good Fiscal Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese budget was closely
observed in the first half of this year with the fiscal revenue
outgrowing expenditure by nearly 8.8 percentage points, according
to the Ministry of Finance (MOF).
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that the national fiscal revenue,
excluding debt income, grew 29.9 percent on a yearly basis in the
first six months to more than 390.1 billion yuan in the first six
months, while fiscal spendings expanded 21.1 percent to 351.2
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The two amounts translated into a fiscal surplus of 38.8
billion yuan for the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on a national conference on fiscal work, the MOF
minister Liu Zhongli on Sunday attributed the rapid revenue growth
to a number of "special factors."
</P>
<P>
The stamp duties on stock trading in the first six months were
considerably more than the same 1996 period, while tax rebates to
exporters decreased, he explained.
</P>
<P>
However, Liu pointed out that some problems still existed in
the first half, such as increasing tax payment delays by
enterprises and unbalanced fiscal revenue growth among different
areas.
</P>
<P>
In some places, fiscal spending expanded to such an extent that
it exceeded revenue increase, noted Liu, who is also
Director-General of the State Administration of Taxation.
</P>
<P>
To solve those problems, Liu urged the fiscal departments at
all levels to beef up management and supervision of the fiscal
revenue and expenditure, in order to make sure that the central
budget deficit will fall below the planned amount, which is 57
billion yuan, four billion yuan less than the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
The minister also called on fiscal and taxation departments to
enhance tax collection, deal a harsh blow to tax evasion and
cheating, and stem unauthorized extension of tax delays and
exemptions.
</P>
<P>
He warned that no new policies for increasing fiscal spending
will be introduced. "Except for subsidies for disaster relief and
grain, no additional spendings should ever be arranged," Liu
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
