<HEADLINE> UN Concerns Over Escalating Hostilities in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Special
Mission to Afghanistan (UNSMA) today expressed its grave concern
over the escalating hostilities in Afghanistan in recent weeks
while calling for an immediate ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the aerial bombing of civilian areas in Kabul
is "most regrettable and deplorable" and it "simply complicates
the already difficult search for peace in Afghanistan," the UNSMA
said in a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations earnestly appeals for the immediate halt of
this aerial bombing of the civilian targets and urges the warring
parties in Afghanistan to cease all forms of hostilities, and to
begin genuine negotiations for a lasting settlement," it said.
</P>
<P>
Forces loyal to former Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood
recaptured on Sunday morning the strategic Bargram airbase and
Charikar, capital of Parwan province, in a strong offensive
against the Islamic Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, several jets belonging to the opposition
forces bombed the Taliban controlled Kabul, killing eight
civilians and injuring many more. 
</P>
