<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elsie Tu: English Lady Dedicated to HK Poor  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- When most Hong Kong residents
started to enjoy weekend on Saturday afternoon, Elsie Tu greeted
her most intense and arduous work in a week.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after a meager lunch of sandwich and cheese, the old
lady, who is already 84, returned to her office for something that
 she has been ceaselessly doing for more than 30 years -- having
interviews with people in trouble and trying to help them out.
</P>
<P>
From 1:30 to 5:30 p.m., she listened patiently to the wishes
and complaints of more than 50 people, examined their cases one by
one, and drafted five letters of application or petition to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Among her visitors were senior citizens walking on sticks, new
mothers carrying babies, young couples with little children, as
well as Filipino maids and Pakistanis. Some of them came a long
way from the "New Territories" and waited a long time to see her.
</P>
<P>
They were very different people, and asked for help in a
variety of things -- from housing to immigration, and from social
welfare to legal aid. But from their faces and eyes one could find
something in common: hearty respect for and firm belief in this
silver-haired English lady.
</P>
<P>
Children, no matter how old they are, could also enter Elsie's
office while their parents were beckoned in. Each of them got
several candies from Elsie's assistant to keep them quiet during
the interview.
</P>
<P>
Until her last client left, Elsie didn't take a single break
throughout the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"We used to have as many as 100 cases and had to work until ten
o'clock at night when we first started," she said. "This is not
too much work for us compared with that."
</P>
<P>
Though her eye sockets had turned red as a result of wearing
glasses and writing papers for too long, she was obviously in high
spirit.
</P>
<P>
Helping the Poor
</P>
<P>
"When I arrived in Hong Kong, there was no democracy, no
justice, no legal aid and no social welfare, nothing," recalled
Elsie, who came here in 1951. "And it was the underprivileged who
suffered most because they did not dare to speak out."
</P>
<P>
She started her efforts to "make amends for the injustices and
inequalities" in a hut area in Kai Tak New Village opposite the
international airport of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Along with others she helped people in need of medical
treatment for minor ailments, and began a school for those who
could not afford fees in other schools.
</P>
<P>
The school, now called Mu Kuang English School and with Elsie
as its supervisor, started from an old army tent and only 30
students. It has developed into one of the most successful private
secondary schools in Kowloon area, with a total of 1,500 students.
</P>
<P>
In early 1963, Elsie made a significant decision in her life --
to campaign for a seat on the Urban Council, the only government
body open to partial election then.
</P>
<P>
"It is most important for the people to have a reasonable way
of living, but sometimes you can't get it except through having
some democratic representation in the government," she talked
about her motives.
</P>
<P>
Even before she was elected into the council, people who
learned her name and ideas from the newspapers started to flock to
her for help, and she still clearly remembered the first major
case she handled.
</P>
<P>
"It was a very cold day, the coldest we had for 50 years," she
said. "A group of people from a large hut area in Jordan Valley
came to me because the government had sent men to smash out their
huts and left all of them, including old people and children, out
in the cold air."
</P>
<P>
It wasn't easy to persuade the senseless bureaucrats in the
government, such as directors of the social welfare and housing
departments, to do anything for those people. With perseverance
and persistent efforts, however, Elsie finally made them agree to
move the people into a place where they could build a new hut.
</P>
<P>
"It was a very big fight and we won it," she said plainly,
adding that the first thing she did after winning the election was
to persuade the Urban Council to pass a policy requiring the
government never to leave any people homeless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elsie Tu: English Lady Dedicated to HK Poor (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
That case also marked the beginning of Elsie's efforts to
develop an efficient system to fight against what she called
"corruption and lack of care by the government under the colonial
system".
</P>
<P>
Every Saturday afternoon, she and her assistants, mostly
volunteers, met with people suffering from various social
problems, recorded their wishes and complaints, and then sought a
solution to their problems from the administration.
</P>
<P>
"Every time we finished the interview, we immediately typed a
letter and sent it to relevant departments, and we would write a
reminder in three weeks if there was no answer," said Elsie.
"Sometimes we had to send two or three reminders."
</P>
<P>
Though there were a lot of difficulties at the beginning, she
said, things have become much easier now, for most members of the
civil service now understand that she will continue to push them
for an answer, even if the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the government's efforts over the past two decades,
we have got rid of a lot of corruption and the government service
is much more responsible now than before," she added. "Our cases
are dealt with much more fairly."
</P>
<P>
Nearly half a million people have gone to Elsie for help since
she went onto the Urban Council in 1963. Some of them represented
groups of people that sometimes numbered more than 100.
</P>
<P>
"We help anyone who comes, no matter what colors or social
status they have," said Elsie. "We have probably helped more than
half of our visitors to find a solution to their problems."
</P>
<P>
Allen Lau, who has served voluntarily as Elsie's part-time
assistant and interpreter for more than 30 years, said that Elsie
was one of the first two local legislators that pioneered in
meeting the public and listening to their problems.
</P>
<P>
Now many people, including District Board members, Urban
Councilors and Legislative Councilors, have followed suit, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I have been working with Elsie for so long because I think she
really serves the people," he added.
</P>
<P>
A jobless old man, who went to Elsie after failing to get
government medical assistance to his badly ill wife, said to her:
"When I saw your name, I saw hope again."
</P>
<P>
Family Influence
</P>
<P>
Born to a worker's family in June 1913, Elsie grew up to
experience the great economic depression that hit the world in the
late 1920s, and saw a lot of unemployment, hunger and miseries
among the people around her.
</P>
<P>
"My father was a socialist. He always hoped that I would one
day become a member of the parliament and work for the rights of
the underprivileged," she said.
</P>
<P>
At first, however, she chose a different road by becoming a
missionary worker.
</P>
<P>
She sailed to China in late 1947 and never had the chance to
see again her beloved father, who died the next year. But the
marks of her father's thinking and expectation have never perished
on her mind.
</P>
<P>
She soon became very disappointed about the missionary work
because she found that religion couldn't solve problems.
</P>
<P>
"So I gave it up and continued what my father wanted me to do,
that is, to work for the people through the policies and political
means," she said.
</P>
<P>
However, it was Hong Kong, instead of Britain, that had become
her arena to turn her father's wishes into reality.
</P>
<P>
"Though I was wrongly interested in being a missionary, it has
also done good in a way because it brought me out to Hong Kong,
where I had been able to work against the injustices of the
colonial government here," said Elsie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elsie Tu: English Lady Dedicated to HK Poor (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following her entry into the Urban Council in 1963, she won
eight consecutive re-elections until 1995, and joined the
Legislative Council twice in 1988 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, she became a member of the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR), Hong Kong's transitional legislature after its
return to China on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
"Having interviews with the people is very useful to my
legislative work, for you must first find out the problems before
you can try to solve them through legislation," said Elsie.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Elsie married a Chinese -- Andrew Tu Hsueh Kwei, who
had been her co-worker ever since the founding of the "tent
school" in 1954.
</P>
<P>
"We have the same interests and the same careers, and he has
always been a strong support to my work," Elsie said of her
husband, who is also the founder of the Hong Kong Branch of the
Samaritans.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the local media, Andrew Tu gave a
definition to the "same interests" between him and Elsie -- to
promote education and work for the benefits of the community.
</P>
<P>
Social Recognition
</P>
<P>
On July 2, one day after the founding of the HKSAR, the SAR
government bestowed the Grand Bauhinia Medal (GBM), the highest
award in Hong Kong's new honor system, to people who had made
outstanding contributions to the local community. Elsie was the
only foreign national among the 12 recipients.
</P>
<P>
A brief citation released by the SAR government to all local
media introduced Elsie as the one who "has stood up for the
interests of grassroots members of the Hong Kong community for
several decades".
</P>
<P>
"I find it unbelievable that I was among the first twelve to
receive the GBM, especially as I'm not Chinese," Elsie said. "It
shows that the Chinese are still friendly to the British people
and do not discriminate on race, in spite of the colonial attitude
of some British officials such as the last governor (Chris
Patten)."
</P>
<P>
She also became the first foreigner to acquire the status of
HKSAR permanent resident, which, along with the medal-winning, was
described by the local media as "Madam Tu's double happiness".
</P>
<P>
Though it was during a five-day public holiday from June 28 to
July 2, the Department of Immigration of the HKSAR managed to
grant Elsie the right of abode on the early morning of July 1, so
as to ensure her eligibility to be sworn into the PLC.
</P>
<P>
Hung on the walls of Elsie's office at the Mu Kuang English
School are several silk banners and bronze plates, all carrying
words of gratitude from people she helped.
</P>
<P>
"Elsie has nearly one hundred of these things, and the office
will be too small to hang all of them out," one of her assistants
said.
</P>
<P>
But for Elsie, some smaller and plainer things appeared to be
more unforgettable and brought her greater joy than medals and
banners did.
</P>
<P>
Once when she took a taxi, the driver, a man in his 40s,
refused to take her fare. "Thank you very much," he said. "You
helped my mom when I was a kid."
</P>
<P>
When she went shopping, she often met store owners calling her
their friend and offering a cheaper price for whatever she bought.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest reward for me is on the faces of those people I
have helped," Elsie once told her friends.
</P>
<P>
Among millions of "thanks" she received over the past four
decades, she was most deeply touched by a Christmas card from a
teenage boy she had helped to save from prison.
</P>
<P>
"Thank you, you're always so kind and considerate in whatever
you do," said the card. "The world will become prettier with more
people like you."
</P>
<P>
"Maybe I don't deserve such a high praise," said Elsie. "But
this is the goal we are striving after."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese FM Leaves for Pakistan, India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko
Ikeda left here today on a 10-day Asian tour which will first take
him to Pakistan and India before attending meetings of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During his visits to Pakistan and India, Ikeda will hold talks
with Pakistani President Farooq Leghari and Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub, and with new Indian President K. Narayanan and Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister Inder Gujral, Japanese government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda is the first Japanese foreign minister to visit Pakistan
in nine years and India in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda is expected to urge Pakistani and Indian leaders to sign
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) as part of a global
nuclear nonproliferation campaign.
</P>
<P>
He will also give Japan's support to economic reforms in both
countries, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
After visiting Pakistan and India, Ikeda will fly to Kuala
Lumpur to attend an ASEAN Regional Forum meeting and an ASEAN
foreign ministerial meeting with the regional group's dialogue
partners.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda will return to Tokyo on July 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
