<HEADLINE> Technology Transfer Urged for Boosting Coffee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti called on experts attending the 17th International
Conference on Coffee Science to make efforts in improving coffee
quality by worldwide transfer of technology.
</P>
<P>
"Researchers and scientists must make sure that the
technologies and knowledge they generate reach the end users," he
said at the conference opened today.
</P>
<P>
It is very necessary to create "effective networks for easy
flow of information across national boundaries," the vice
president noted.
</P>
<P>
"Through better coordination and collaboration we can improve
quality of services we give to farmers, processors and
consumers," said Darius Mbela, Kenyan Minister for Agriculture,
Livestock Development and Marketing on the same occasion.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 experts from over 40 coffee producing and
consuming countries in the world attended the meeting to end on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to discuss the worldwide trend of
coffee production and consumption, as well as the latest results
of research on coffee.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is the third African country to host the biennial
meeting, which is organized by the International Scientific
Coffee Association founded in Paris 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Coffee trade has a turnover of 10 billion U.S. Dollars
annually, making coffee the second most traded commodity in the
world after oil, said Saitoti. 
</P>
