<HEADLINE> Afghan General Visits Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's National, Islamic
United Front leader General Abdulmalek arrived here today to
exchange views with Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani
on latest development in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that General
Abdulmalek, who has been leading forces in northern Afghanistan
against the take-over by the Taliban of capital Kabul, is on an
official two-day visit and was received at the airport by Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Abdulmalek's entourage include Foreign
Minister Abdulrahim Ghafourzehi and several other senior officials
of the alliance battling the Kabul rule.
</P>
<P>
Abdulmalek was quoted by the report as saying that the goal
behind his visit to Iran was to consolidate friendship and
brotherhood between the Iranian and Afghan nations.
</P>
<P>
He said that forces under his command were now behind the
gates of Kabul and were busy consolidating their positions in
cooperation with people.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that Afghan people have not accepted Taliban's
authority as it is evident in public uprisings in Kabul and
other Afghan cities.
</P>
<P>
Velayati for his part said that considering the unity and
solidarity among national and Islamic forces in northern
Afghanistan it is hoped that civil war would come to an
end in a near future.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the need for a halt to foreign meddling in
Afghanistan's internal affairs and reiterated that no military
solution could be forecast for the Afghan problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that Afghanistan was a country made up of various
tribes and for this reason no single group could impose its
will on others.
</P>
<P>
The defeat not long ago of the Taliban in Mazar-e Sharif,
biggest city in the north, and its surroundings in which Shiite
and Esmaeli Mujahideen played an effective role in consolidating
the status the anti-Taliban alliance which is supported by Iran.
</P>
