<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Confident of Achieving Economic Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines can achieve the 7-8
percent economic growth rate and the 6-6.5 inflation rate set by
the government for the year despite the peso's devaluation, a
senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We are well on track with our targets. It is too early for any
changes," Economic Development Secretary Cielito Habito said in a
mid-year economic review sponsored by the Philippine Chamber of
Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Habito expressed optimism that the country's economy would
perform better during the next quarters due to the recovery of
manufacturing sector and exports, the increase of real investments
and the better performance of the agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
The country's gross national product grew by 6.1 percent during
the first quarter of the year, showing signs of a slowdown when
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Habito said the inflation impact of the depreciation of the
peso would not be substantial because the exchange rate between
the peso and the U.S. dollar would not depreciate much.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists believed that the economy would slow
down this year and the inflation rate would reach at least 8.5
percent following the peso's devaluation.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted in Metro Manila showed that of the 17 kinds
of basic goods, prices of five commodities had increased while oil
prices and power rate are expected to rise later this month.
</P>
<P>
The peso has devalued by 10 percent since the Philippine
Central Bank announced the de facto devaluation of the currency on
July 11 after failing to fend it off speculative attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
