<HEADLINE> Taylor Well Ahead in Liberian Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Early results of Saturday's
Liberian presidential election shows that Charles Taylor, the
former warlord who started the civil war seven years ago, is well
ahead of other candidates in the race for presidency.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here quoted electoral authority in Monrovia
as saying that of the almost half of the votes counted so far,
Taylor won about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
If the situation continues, Taylor will have the 51 percent
majority of votes needed for him to be the new Liberian
president, and a run-off election scheduled for August 2 will not
be needed.
</P>
<P>
Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, a former senior official with the
United Nations and the only woman in the 13 candidates, is the
runner-up. But it is believed that she is lagging far behind
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
The turnout of voters in Saturday's election is said to be
very massive, which is estimated to be about 80 percent of the
710,000 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
With nearly 11,000 west African peace-keeping forces providing
security at every polling station, the election is said to be
very peaceful, smooth and in good order.
</P>
<P>
So far, international observers, including those from the
United Nations, the European Union as well as the neighbouring
west African countries have expressed their satisfaction over the
conduct of the election.
</P>
<P>
But some people cautioned that there is no celebration until
the final result is out and accepted by all the contenders.
</P>
<P>
General Sani Abacha, the Nigerian head of state and chairman
of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) which
has been playing a key role in the Liberian peace process, has
urged the Liberians to accept the verdict of the election.
</P>
<P>
A positive approach to the election result is the only way to
achieve reconciliation, reconstruction and rehabilitation of the
war-devastated Liberia, Abacha said in a goodwill message sent to
Liberian people on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
