<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Africa's Gold Industry Faces up to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's gold
industry, believed to be the biggest in the world, is facing
unprecedented difficulties following gold slump to below 320 U.S.
Dollars an ounce in world market early this month.
</P>
<P>
If the precious metal does not stabilize in the next 12
months, thousands of jobs will be lost on mines across the
country, local industrial sources warned over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
About 345,000 South Africans, most of them black, reportedly
depend on jobs in the gold industry for their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
According to South Africa's National Union of Mineworkers
(NUM), up to about 100,000 mine workers may lose their job to
keep the gold industry viable.
</P>
<P>
Currently, nine out of 38 gold mines in South Africa are
considered marginal, with seven actually making a loss, informed
sources said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa once had a prosperous period in the early 1970s
when its gold production amounted to more than 1,000 tons in
1970.
</P>
<P>
However, as time goes on, the glittering industry in the
country has begun fading as the annual gold production has
decreased remarkablely in recent years, even to 496 tons in 1996,
the lowest in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
South Africa holds an estimated 40 percent of the world's gold
reserves, but its labor-intensive deep-level mining is more
costly than the surface mining in the United States and
Australia, two gold giants in the world.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sources attributed the large scale gold drop to
the government's subsidy cut for the industry, aging equipment,
disputes between miners and mine owners and a sequence of mine
accidents.
</P>
<P>
Besides, South African mines do not operate for 90 days a year
-- due to a Sunday mining ban, holidays and shift arrangements,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The problems have apparently hindered the development of South
Africa's gold industry and directly resulted in huge losses in
gold mines. The depression has made the industrialists cut some
120,000 jobs in gold mining during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Local observers pointed out that further lay-offs could damage
confidence in the Government of National Unity led by President
Nelson Mandela, which has promised people jobs, housing and a
better life.
</P>
<P>
To revitalize the gold industry and meet the challenge of gold
slump in global market, the NUM has just reached an accord with
the Chamber of Mines to increase the country's gold production
and to have mine workers better paid. The agreed aim is to
increase gold production by 90 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Chamber of Mines will increase
mineworkers' wages from 10 percent to 25 percent on condition
that productivity and production targets are met.
</P>
<P>
NUM Secretary-General Kgalema Motlanthe described the accord
as a "significant breakthrough", saying it would pave the way for
sustained growth in the gold mining industry.
</P>
<P>
NUM President James Motlatsi also noted that the agreement
would contribute to preserving the present level of employment in
the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
