<HEADLINE> S. Africa Repatriates 82,000 Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- About 82,000 illegal
immigrants have been sent back to their countries of origin,
mainly African states, in the past six months, according to South
African Home Affairs Department officials.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,400 ilegal immigrants are repatriated each week
and the figure could more than double within the next three
months, they said.
</P>
<P>
The biggest group of illegal immigrants are reportedly
Mozambicans.
</P>
<P>
Of all detained illegal immigrants, 84.5 percent are from
Mozambique, 10.7 percent from Zimbabwe, 1.2 percent from Malawi,
3.4 percent from other African states and 0.2 percent from the
rest of the world, an official survey shows.
</P>
<P>
South African civil organizations claimed that there are an
estimated eight million illegal immigrants in the country.
</P>
<P>
South African Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi has
warned that failure to curb the flood of illegal immigrants would
impoverish the country.
</P>
<P>
If all illegal aliens were removed, South Africa's
unemployment problem, one of the most serious in the country,
would be closer to a solution, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
