<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Inflation Rate Declines to 12.8 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's overall month-on-month
inflation rate fell to 12.8 percent in June from 17.2 percent in
May, according to the latest issue of the Economic Review.
</P>
<P>
The monthly review by the Central Bank of Kenya attributed the
fall to improved weather conditions which have resulted in a rise
in food supply.
</P>
<P>
The month-on-month inflation in food prices also declined to
13.2 percent in June compared with 17.5 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicted that the inflation rate would decline
further to reach the single digit range by early 1998 on the
account of increased output from agricultural related sectors in
1997.
</P>
<P>
It is critical to reach the objective, the bank noted, adding
government borrowing from the Central Bank of Kenya should be
kept on no more than 5 percent of the most recent audited
government gross recurrent revenue.
</P>
<P>
To confine inflation to single digit rate in the 1997/98
fiscal year, according to the Economic Review, the bank will
ensure that the expansion of money supply drop from 13.5 percent
in April to no more than 11 percent by June 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
