<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Nigerians Under Poverty Line, UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Two out of five Nierians live below
the poverty line and one third of the country's population lack
health service, according to the 1996 Human Development Report of
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two-thirds of Nigerians do not have safe water and
sanitation and 47.5 percent are illiterate, said the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Nigeria ranks 141st out of 175
countries in consideration of their human development index which
measures a country's achievements in terms of life expectancy,
educational attainment and adjusted real income.
</P>
<P>
Chief Ernest Shonekan, ex-head of state, acknowledged that a
world survey in 1992 showed about 34 percent of Nigeria's
population were estimated to be poor.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now has moved into one of the world's 50 poorest
countries with its per capita income dropping from 1,160 U.S.
dollars in 1980 to just 260 dollars in 1995, said Shonekan, the
current chairman of the Vision 2010 Committee in charge of
long-term socio-economic planning.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty has increased over the past few years in line with
the deterioration in the economic and social conditions of the
country," he admitted at the launching of the report in the
capital Abuja over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
According to him, his committee has been undertaking "a
soul-searching" exercise to appraise Nigeria's current
circumstances so as to "chart a better future for it in the 21st
century and beyond".
</P>
<P>
Minister of National Planning Chief Ayo Ogunlade also said
there is an urgent need to deliberately pursue pragmatic policies
and strategies capable of accelerating growth and development.
</P>
<P>
"Given Nigeria's rich human and material resources and
potential, our great nation should not belong to the group of
countries with very low human development profile," he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP report, according to the agency's resident
representative in Nigeria, Babashola Chinsman, is an attempt to
examine the specific causes of poverty in the country and to
advance corrective actions and proposals.
</P>
<P>
The six-point agenda of the report for action to eradicate
poverty in Nigeria includes compulsory education for all and
eradication of illiteracy, and universal access to safe water and
primary health care.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for increased opportunities of employment for
the masses and enhancing the share of women in economic and
social empowerment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Tax Big Firms for 3.6 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The French government announced
today that it will draw in the remaining months of the year 22
billion francs (about 3.6 billion U.S. dollars) of profits from
big enterprises to cut the country's public deficit.
</P>
<P>
France's public deficit is expected to stand at 3.5-3.7 percent
of its gross domestic product by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The measure, described by former Finance Minister Jean Arthuis
as one of "crushing the nest egg," remained the only choice for
the Socialist government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin to meet
the three percent public deficit criteria set by the Maastricht
treaty to join the euro at the beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The French government will also cut 10 billion francs (about
1.6 billion dollars) in public spending, including two billion
francs (about 320 million dollars) on military spending, announced
the Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after the Public Finance Audit
published its evaluation report on France's finance situation,
saying that the country will over-spend 32 billion francs (about
5.3 billion dollars) this year, if no measure was taken to cut
spending and raise state revenue.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises to be touched by the new profits tax include
those with more than 50 billion francs (about 8.3 billion dollars)
of transactions or with long term profits. Strauss-Kahn said that
the new tax will be 15 percent more than the original one.
</P>
<P>
The new measure is expected to be greatly resented by France's
entrepreneurs, who hate to see enterprises become the "milk cows"
of the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0080 </DOCNO>
