<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Reports 15 Percent Rise in 1996 Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
boosted spending to a record high in 1996 as the government
increased allocations for subsidies, an official report showed
today.
</P>
<P>
The total expenditure reached 19.6 billion U.S. dollars last
year, a more than 15 percent rise compared with 17 billion dollars
in 1995, said the latest report issued by the UAE Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Most of the spending increase that year went to allocations for
subsidies and government transfers abroad, which jumped to about
4.7 billion dollars from 2 billion dollars in the previous year,
the report showed.
</P>
<P>
New jobs and promotions boosted allocations for salaries to
civil servants from 3.2 billion dollars in 1995 to 3.4 billion
dollars in 1996, while spending on import of goods and services
rose slightly to around 4.657 billion dollars from nearly 4.655
billion dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report gave no specific figures on defense spending, which
was among the highest in the world as compared with its gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
But under an item classified as other expenditures, there was
an increase to 2.85 billion dollars in 1996 from 2.27 billion
dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report showed development spending, involving allocations
for new ventures and projects under construction, declined to
around 2.77 billion dollars from 3.04 billion dollars in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Loans and grants were also cut to nearly 1.1 billion dollars in
1996 from 1.57 billion dollars in 1995, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
Despite the high expenditure, the country's financial deficit
shrank to 4.85 billion dollars last year from 5.37 billion dollars
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
This is mainly attributed to high revenues in 1996 resulting
from a growth in the country's oil and gas earning of 10.1 billion
dollars from around 8.7 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is among the world's top oil powers, producing nearly
2.16 million barrels per day. Crude and gas exports fetch it more
than 12 billion dollars annually but the income is shared on a 40
to 60 percent basis with foreign partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
