<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Down in Light Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
followed the lead of Wall Street today to close down in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed down 30.8 points,
just over one percent, at 2,653.4.
</P>
<P>
"It was just on the back of the Dow having a little bit of a
hiccup on Friday and we have followed suit, the selling today was
really just a bit of profit taking," Henderson Charlton Jones
broker Brett O'Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
Despite general increases in commodities prices in combination
with a low Australian dollar, mining and resource stocks fell
today.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 21.6 points to 1,426.7 while
the all industrials fell 43.7 points to 4,233.1.
</P>
<P>
Market bellwether BHP fell markedly by 46 cents to 18.10
Australian dollars, resource company WMC fell 17 cents to 7.70
Australian dollars and Rio Tinto dropped 38 cents to 21.42
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 1.4 points to 1,311.7 while gold bullion
closed in Sydney at 327.95 US dollars an ounce from 324.00 US
dollars on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lend Lease tumbled 49 cents to 27.81 Australian dollars while
Coca-Cola Amatil shed some of the huge gains it made at the end of
last week to fall 67 cents to 15.91 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank rose in late trading to defy falls at other major
banks, prompting speculation from some brokers of a possible
resolution of the long-running Bank of Melbourne merger probe by
the Australian Competition and Consumer Commission.
</P>
<P>
Westpac increased eight cents to 7.98 Australian dollars while
NAB fell 16 cents to 19.22 Australian dollars, ANZ dropped nine to
10.06 Australian dollars and Commonwealth Bank fell 2.6 cents to
16.22 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 281.16 million shares traded worth
670.36 million Australian dollars (496.06 million US dollars),
with falls outnumbering rises 678 to 400.  
</P>
</TEXT>
