<HEADLINE> Top Unionist to Seek Reassurance from Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's powerful
pro-British Unionist party leader said today he would seek
reassurances from Prime Minister Tony Blair that the Irish
Republican Army would have to hand over or decommission some
weapons at the start of a substantial negotiation.
</P>
<P>
"Reassurances are very cheap. What counts is what is down in
black and white and what is going to happen," David Trimble,
leader of the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), told local reporters
hours before he met Blair at Downing Street on the new ceasefire
of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
The new truce, which took effect at noon Sunday, allows IRA's
political wing Sinn Fein to gain a place in the substantial talks
on Northern Ireland's future.
</P>
<P>
Such reassurances would "have to be underwritten by the Irish
government," a co-sponsor of the negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Although UUP is strongly opposed to talks with Sinn Fein,
Trimble suggested that his party would not walk out of the Belfast
peace talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"I said after I came out of Downing Street last Thursday that
we are not of a mind to walk out," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was Trimble's first public comment since the IRA declared a
ceasefire at the weekend in its 28-year war in a bid to earn Sinn
Fein a seat at peace talks in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Trimble also said the British government is showing duplicity
in handling the issue of how guerrillas should surrender their
arms.
</P>
<P>
"We are dealing with duplicity from the Northern Ireland Office
on a massive scale," BBC radio quoted Trimble as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the IRA had called the truce because Sinn Fein had been
given to understand by Britain that it would not have to secure
the handover of any IRA arms during the talks.
</P>
<P>
"They (Sinn Fein) interpret it as a guarantee that they
don't have to carry out any decommissioning at all," Trimble
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
