<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buoyant International Business Fuels Siemens' Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Siemens AG, Germany's largest
electronics and engineering group, today reported
more-than-expected growth in the first nine months of this fiscal
year, thanks exclusively to buoyant international business.
</P>
<P>
During the first nine months from October 1, 1996 to September
30, 1997, worldwide orders of Siemens rose by 14 percent to 82.8
billion Duetch marks (about 46.3 billion U.S. dollars) and sales
rose by 10 percent to 71.2 billion marks (about 39.8 billion
dollars). Net income for the period was up three percent to 1.705
billion marks (about 953 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to an interim report released by Siemens on Monday,
the company's growth was generated exclusively by international
business, where orders rose by 23 percent to 55.6 billion marks
(about 31 billion dollars) and sales climbed 18 percent to 46.3
billion marks (about 25.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The company's business in Germany, in contrast, edged off
slightly with domestic orders totaling 27.2 billion marks (about
15.2 billion dollars) and sales, 24.9 billion marks (about 13.9
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
International business now accounted for 67 percent of the
total business volume of Siemens, which is celebrating its 150
anniversary this year.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that while communications and
information segments continued to drive growth at Siemens, the
company's medical engineering and transportation systems units
were still in red due to the massive restructuring programs, and
the good earnings of the components segment lay below last year's
figures due to extreme price deterioration.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the company's traditional news conference in Berlin
on Monday, Siemens President Heinrich v. Pierer predicted that the
company's orders for the whole year would range from 106 to 108
billion marks (about 59.2 to 60.3 billion dollars), and sales
would hit 100 to 102 billion marks (about 55.9 to 57 billion
dollars), marking the first time they exceeded 100 billion marks
level.
</P>
<P>
On expectations for fiscal 1998, V. Pierer stated: "In contrast
to the current year, we expect a significant rise in net income,
one that will be notably higher than the growth in business
volume." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
