<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Pullout not Precondition for Ceasefire: Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Philippine government
official today denied the pullout of government troops in the
southern Philippines is a precondition for ceasefire between the
military and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF).
</P>
<P>
Philippine Executive Secretary Ruben Torres said in an
interview with local reporters that there is a need to normalize
the situation in Raja Muda, Pikit, Cotabato province, before the
military pulls out from the place.
</P>
<P>
The national government would like to see that civil
authorities take over Raja Muda where there is still some
conflicts, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire agreement signed by the government and the MILF
last Friday takes effect today and so far no violation of the
ceasefire has been reported.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces of the Philippines and the MILF will monitor
the situation if there are any violations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Torres said that the government's anti-kidnapping
operation in central Mindanao will go on despite the ceasefire
because it is "simple enforcement of the law".  
</P>
</TEXT>
