<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Increases in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade in June
increased by 5.3 percent on a three month moving average basis at
current prices, with the non-oil domestic exports expanding by 4.4
percent after a marginal growth rate of 0.8 percent a month
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today that on
a monthly basis, non-oil domestic exports grew by 8.8 percent
following a decline of one percent in May and an increase of 5.9
percent in April this year.
</P>
<P>
"This was the highest monthly growth rate recorded since May
last year, though partly because June 1996 export figure was below
trend levels", the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
It said that re-exports continued to grow steadily by 7.5
percent on a monthly basis in June this year, due mainly to strong
growth in re-exports of electronic products. Non-oil imports rose
by 2.8 percent in the month.
</P>
<P>
With the 4.4 percent expansion, non-oil domestic exports
increased to a level of 7.5 billion Singapore dollars, or about
5.2 billion US dollars, in June this year, as exports to the
European Union and Hong Kong recorded a double digit growth of
11.3 percent and 11.1 percent respectively, the TDB noted.
</P>
<P>
Oil domestic exports grew by one percent in June, partly
because of higher shipments of high speed diesel oil to Hong Kong,
it said, adding that re-exports recorded an increase of 9.2
percent in June on a three month moving average basis, reaching a
level of 6.2 billion Singapore dollars (about 4.3 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In June, imports increased by 4.7 percent to 15.9 billion
Singapore dollars (about 10.97 billion US dollars). The TDB said
that the increases in imports were reflected in imports of
integrated circuits, computer parts and peripherals, disk drives,
and other electronic products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
