<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin will take note this morning of
the report by the audit on the public financial deficit of France
this year, which is expected to stand between 3.5 percent and 3.7
percent of the gross domestic product. The government will
announce a series of measures to reduce the deficit in order to
keep on the track toward the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
-- The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
(OECD) said in a latest report that immigration does not pose as a
problem for economic recovery and employment. France, whose frontier
control is among the tightest in the world, did not see its
unemployment rate drop while the number of immigrants fell
considerably over the past few years. Britain, which saw massive
inflow of immigrants in recent years, experienced a resumption of
economic growth, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin will raise benefit tax on big
enterprises while saving the families from the "euro tax" to be
imposed to meet the Maastricht treaty public deficit criteria of 3
percent of gross domestic product (GDP). The public deficit of
France this year is expected to be around 3.5 percent of the GDP,
or about 30 billion francs (5 billion U.S. dollars), according to
government sources.
</P>
<P>
-- Former Finance Minister Jean Arthuis has denounced the plan
by the Socialist government to raise tax on big enterprises to
reduce public deficit, saying that the Socialists arrived in power
only to "crush the nest egg." Julien Dray, leader of the splinter
Socialist Left party which joins the ruling coalition, also warned
that only asking enterprises to make contributions to the effort
to join the euro could be "dangerous." 
</P>
</TEXT>
