<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reports Sound Financial Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The financial situation in this
economic center of China was generally good in the first half of
this year, the local branch of the central bank said in a report.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, bank loans increased appropriately,
government treasury bonds were issued smoothly and the level of
financial opening-up was raised, the Shanghai branch of the
People's Bank of China said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that bank deposits increased by 73.3 billion
yuan (about 8.8 billion US dollars) between January and June, 16.1
billion yuan more than during the same period of last year. Bank
loans rose 28.3 billion yuan in the six months, or 2.7 billion
yuan more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also show the stock market capitalization in
the city reached 861.2 billion yuan by the end of June, a surge of
57.2 percent from the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Six of the nine overseas banks approved by the central bank to
deal in renminbi yuan on a trial basis in Shanghai's Pudong New
Area officially and successfully launched the new business in the
first six months, which has helped ease the overseas-funded
enterprises' shortage of yuan funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Company Officials in Sichuan Dismissed for Mismanagement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Four senior officials of a major
steel company in Sichuan Province in southwest China were
dismissed for their role in the company's hefty financial loss
during the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials of the Great Wall Special Steel Corp.,
including former Chairman Liu Lizhong, former General Manager Lu
Yuxing and Zhai Guangyao, former secretary of the company's
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, lost their jobs for
their mismanagement which the caused the company to lose 300
million yuan (about $37.5 million) in the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government ordered the individuals be removed
from office. While making investigations in the company, Sichuan
Provincial Governor Song Baorui asked new company executives to
quicken the pace of the reform in reducing the number of redundant
workers and improving efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The heavy deficit makes the company the biggest money-loser
among all state-run enterprises in Sichuan. It has been unable to
pay wages to its 28,000 employees since March.
</P>
<P>
The company, one of ten major special steel producers in
the country, incurred a deficit of 23.97 million yuan last year,
and the downward spiral continued through the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is considering giving preferential
treatment to the company to help get it back on its feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
