<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Imports from Arab Countries Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's imports from Arab countries
increased by 5.5 percent during the first three months of this
year, local English language newspaper The Egyptian Gazette
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The country's imports from the Arab world amounted to 425.3
million Egyptian pounds (125 million U.S. dollars) in the
January-March period, compared with 403 million pounds (118.5
million dollars) a year ago, the paper quoted an economic report
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia topped the list with exports to Egypt valued at
267 million pounds (78.5 million dollars) in the first quarter,
said the report issued by the Central Agency of Statistics and
Mobilization.
</P>
<P>
Libya came second, exporting 38.9 million pounds (11.4 million
dollars) worth of goods to Egypt, followed by the United Arab
Emirates, from where Egypt purchased 29.6 million pounds (8.7
million dollars) of goods.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Egypt's imports from Lebanon, Morocco, Oman,
Somalia and Tunisia had decreased during the first quarter of this
year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been calling for expanding the limited inter-Arab
trade, whose volume falls below 10 percent of their trade with
countries outside the Arab world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
