<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Police Uncover Bomb Factory in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian security forces
have uncovered a bomb-making factory in Beit Sahur near
Bethlehem, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The discovery came as part of a Palestinian investigation into
the death of an Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) activist, who
blew himself up while making a bomb last week, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, 30 kilograms of TNT and Israeli army
uniforms were found in the factory. A number of explosives were
connected to timing devices.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian police in Bethlehem said it was no doubt that the
discovery would help prevent further terrorist attacks against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The discovery also came under the backdrop of Israel's
increasing pressure on the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to
crack down on terrorism following the arrest of three Palestinian
policemen by Israeli forces last week.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that the Palestinian policemen were attempting
to carry out a shooting attack against a Jewish settlement near
the West Bank city of Nablus. Israeli government took advantage of
the incident by accusing the Palestinian police of organizing
riots and terrorist attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli pressure, Palestinian police have arrested
four policemen, including Nablus police Assistant Commander Jihad
Massimi. But Israel further demanded the PNA to arrest Ghazi
Jabali, Commander of Palestinian police in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, who was charged for masterminding the planned attack.
</P>
<P>
However, Palestinian officials have shrugged off the Israeli
evidence concerning so-called Palestinian police involvement in
terrorism activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
