<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbawe's Ex-Combatants Demand Government's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The meetings between Zimbabwe's
ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF)
politburo members and ex-combatants on Sunday throughout the
country's regional centers mostly turned nasty, the daily "The
Herald" reported today.
</P>
<P>
At all the meetings, ex-combatants accused the ruling party of
abandoning them and demanded that the lump sum payments from the
war victims' compensation fund be resumed without fail.
</P>
<P>
Three ministers addressing the Harare meeting had to be
whisked out of the ZANU-PF headquarters hall through the back
entrance when ex-combatants blocked the exits after invading the
stage where the ministers and other dignitaries were seated.
</P>
<P>
Politburo member and Minister of Defense Moven Mahachi,
Minister of Sport, Recreation and Culture Witness Mangwende and
Minister of Public Service, Labour and Social Welfare Florence
Chitauro were occasionally shouted down and booed as they tried
to explain reasons for stopping the payments and what the
government and the ruling party had put in place instead.
</P>
<P>
At one point a female ex-combatant dumped her baby into
Chitauro's arms challenging her to feed the baby. She was later
persuaded to take back the child. By that time emotions were
running high, there was a danger of violence.
</P>
<P>
After ensuring that checks which have been held back would be
disbursed today, the three ministers were escorted out through
the back, leaving their cars behind.
</P>
<P>
The story was the same elsewhere in the country. The
ex-combatants, who met delegations headed by politburo members,
were angry and complained the same as their colleagues but kept
their emotions in check although at times they bubbled to the
surface.
</P>
<P>
"This shows a lack of trust between the government and
ex-combatants," said The Herald today in a commentary, adding
"Sometimes the ex-combatants even denounced the war veterans
board and demanded that its leadership be fired."
</P>
<P>
"The sooner a dignified closed-door meeting with the
leadership of the fighters is arranged, the better," concluded
the country's leading newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
