<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Booms in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in Shanghai,
China's major economic center, has been developing rapidly in
recent years, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that there were 62,000 private
businesses in Shanghai by the end of May, with the number of
employees reaching more than 657,000. The two figures were 26 and
nearly 13 times the numbers in 1991 respectively.
</P>
<P>
An analysis of the statistics shows that the average registered
capital of the private businesses here is 596,000 yuan (about
71,000 US dollars), which was 14.4 times that of 1991 and about 20
percent more than the national average. The total registered
capital volume of the private enterprises surged to 32.1 billion
yuan last year from 290 million yuan in 1992. The output value of
the private sector reached 8.77 billion yuan in 1996, more than
twice the 1992 figure.
</P>
<P>
"The private sector of Shanghai has embarked on a path for
sustained and rapid development and has contributed positively to
the city's economic development and social stability," said Gu
Shunren, deputy director-general of the Shanghai Municipal
Administration for Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
He noted that private businesses in Shanghai turned in 1.2
billion yuan in taxes in 1996, about 4.2 percent of Shanghai's
local fiscal revenue. In some districts and counties, private
enterprises account for more than 30 percent of the revenue.
</P>
<P>
The private sector, whose payroll of 650,000 workers makes up
nearly 10 percent of Shanghai's labor force, has also absorbed
more than 100,000 displaced workers from the state-owned
enterprises. As private businesses are mainly located in the
outskirts, they have also created jobs for some 300,000 farmers.
</P>
<P>
Gu said that Shanghai will take further measures to support and
encourage the growth of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Private enterprises can buy over, hold a stake in and lease
state-owned enterprises in order to participate in the reform and
restructuring of the state-owned sector, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
