<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN: No Hasty Decision Over Aid to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said here today ASEAN will not make a hasty
decision on whether it should suspend aid to Cambodia in the wake
of the latest political crisis in that country.
</P>
<P>
"If we need to assist them, why not?" he told reporters after
opening a three-day Second ASEAN Congress organized by the
Malaysian Institute of Strategic and International Studies
celebrating 30th anniversary of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who is also ASEAN Standing Committee Chairman, said
the 30-year-old regional grouping would have to consider carefully
whether it should suspend its aid to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN, which presently groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, has been giving
aid to Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar in the form of training and
other technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said he would wait for Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas to brief the ASEAN foreign ministers on the outcome of the
meetings with Cambodian head of state King Norodom Sihanouk, First
Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Alatas, together with his counterparts, Prachuab Chaiyasan of
Thailand and Domingo Siazon of the Philippines, had been
dispatched by ASEAN as special envoys to meet the Cambodian
leaders.
</P>
<P>
On the timing of Cambodia's membership into ASEAN, Abdullah
said, "I have never given any dates." "Some decisions will be
taken in this regard" at the foreign ministers' meeting, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Our vision is still the vision of ASEAN 10," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in his keynote address at the congress, Abdullah said
"unfortunately the recent events in Cambodia have forced us to
revise our plans and to defer the admission of Cambodia into the
grouping."  
</P>
</TEXT>
