<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Holds SOM, ASC Meetings in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials
and Standing Committee members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) began their two-day separate meetings here
today to prepare for a ministerial conference scheduled to start
on July 24.
</P>
<P>
They will examine the issues, ranging from political and
security cooperation to economic development in member countries,
to be discussed by their foreign ministers at a two-day meeting,
ASEAN sources said.
</P>
<P>
High on the agenda is the admission of new members Laos and
Myanmar on July 23, thus expanding ASEAN membership to include all
the countries in Southeast Asia except Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN had planned to admit all the three countries at the
30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM) this week, to realize the
long-cherished dream of its founding fathers that the ASEAN would
one day embrace all nations of Southeast Asia in active
cooperation for regional peace, security and common prosperity.
</P>
<P>
But the plan was disrupted by factional fighting between the
forces of Cambodian Co-Prime Ministers Hun Sen and Norodom
Ranariddh on July 5 and 6. At a special foreign ministers meeting
earlier this month, the ASEAN decided to defer Cambodia's
admission because of the fighting, which resulted in the ouster of
First Prime Minister Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the ASEAN to mediate an end to the fighting and
restoration of the coalition government in Cambodia have so far
failed to achieve any results as Hun Sen, who is now in control in
Phnom Penh, refused to accept any outside mediation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas,
Philippine Foreign Minister Domingo Siazon and Thai Foreign
Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn will report to the ministerial
meeting on their talks with Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk in
Beijing, Hun Sen in Phnom Penh and Ranariddh in Bangkok last week.
</P>
<P>
Laos and Myanmar are attending the Senior Officials Meeting
(SOM) for the first time, as observers, before their entry into
the regional grouping, which is at present formed by Brunei,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
However, Foreign Minister Ung Huot of Cambodia, which now
enjoys observer status in the ASEAN, is expected to attend the
ASEAN Regional Forum which will follow the ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN meetings come at a time when the organization is
celebrating its 30th founding anniversary and the failure to admit
Cambodia is widely seen as a damper on what otherwise would be a
nice ASEAN party.
</P>
<P>
But ASEAN officials seem to remain upbeat.
</P>
<P>
"The show will go on," ASEAN Standing Committee (ASC) Chairman
and host Malaysia's Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi was
quoted by the local press as saying earlier. "The postponement of
Cambodia's pending membership does not make the AMM less
significant."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China is wasting no time to
construct its national highway network, giving top priority to
building trunk roads which are playing an increasingly significant
role in the country's social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures from the Ministry of
Communications, by the end of 1996, the country had built 1.18
million km of highway, including over 19,000 km of standard
roadways and 3,400 km of expressways.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 97 percent of towns and townships and 81 percent of
villages in China have highway access.
</P>
<P>
Roads have become one of the most important transportation
routes in the country, handling 88.7 percent of the total
passenger transport and 91 percent of the total cargo shipment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, highways account for 51.1 percent and 13.1 percent
of the entire circulation volume of passengers and goods.
</P>
<P>
In the late 80s, the ministry drafted an outline on building
national trunk-road networks, with a designated total length of
around 35,000 km set to link up Beijing, the Chinese capital city,
with all major cities, offering total roadway access to 600
million people.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, China plans to complete two north-south cross-country
highways and two east-west cross-country roads as well as three
expressways which, respectively, start at Beijing and end at
Zhuhai City in Guangdong Province in the south, Shenyang City,
capital of Liaoning Province in the northeast, and Shanghai,
China's largest industrial city, in the east.
</P>
<P>
According to the official plan, the country will also build
more highways in poverty-stricken areas to make each
state-classified poor county an access to at least one road to
connect with the national trunks in a move to bolster the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, China will have 1.25 million km of
highways, of which 25,000 km will be high-grade roads, including
over 8,000 expressways.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the program, the bottleneck in the
eastern and coastal regions is expected to be eased, while in the
backward areas, mainly in the west and north, the traffic
conditions will also be improved.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the country's highway network will be extended to 1.35
million km, including 40,000 km of high-class roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Mitsui Opening Microelectronics Company In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese-backed
microelectronics company, Mitsui High-Tech (Shanghai) Co. Ltd,
broke ground last month for a building at the Jinqiao Export
Processing Zone at the Pudong New Area in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The company is solely funded by Mitsui High-Tech Inc. of Japan
with an investment of 25 million U.S. dollars. It will produce
integrated circuit frames, metallic cores for various motors,
high-precision metallic molds, precision machinery, IC pieces,
electronic appliances, and other commodities.
</P>
<P>
The company will be finished in early 1998 and will have a
production capacity of 600 million pieces within two years. Half
of its products will be sold in China and the other half will be
for export.
</P>
<P>
Mitsui High-Tech holds 30 percent of the world market for IC
frames, and sold 69.3 billion pieces in 1995 and is expected to
have sales of 76 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
China now depends mainly on imports for its IC frames. The new
company will play an active role in replacing imported products,
reducing expenditures in hard currencies, and in promoting the
development of China's semi-conductor industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
