<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Goods Market Brisk in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China's consumer goods market
remained brisk in the first half of this year, with supply
basically matching demand and price rises dropping.
</P>
<P>
Ding Junfa, spokesman for the Ministry of Internal Trade, told
a press conference today that the retail sales of consumer goods
reached 1.3 trillion yuan (157.38 billion US dollars) between
January and June, a year-on-year increase of 12.1 percent in real
terms. The sales of capital goods amounted to 1.69 trillion yuan,
a year-on-year rise of 8.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The commodity retail price rose by 1.8 percent, a drop of 5.3
percentage points from the hike in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The price for resident consumption increased by 4.1 percent, a
drop of 5.1 percentage points from the growth rate of the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, prices of capital goods fell by 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysis of 609 key commodities shows that the supply and
demand of 545 of the commodities were in a near balance; the
supply of 32 goods fell short of demand, while the supply of other
32 varieties exceeded the needed amount.
</P>
<P>
"The commodity market continues to be a buyer's market," the
spokesman commented.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that the proportion of food consumption
continued to fall in the overall expenditure and consumers have
become more choosy and more name-brand conscious.
</P>
<P>
The first half year also saw new progress in building
supermarkets, chain stores, warehouse markets and commodity
distribution centers.
</P>
<P>
Main problems in the commodity market include a large
stockpile of goods valued at three trillion yuan and unfair
competition conditions, Ding pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Industry Ministry of Thailand is studying the
idea of establishing a Muslim food production complex to cater to
the world's 1.5 billion Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The complex, to be located in southern Thailand which has a
large Muslim community and is near to Muslims-dominated Malaysia,
is part of the ministry's "food for the world" vision, according
to Deputy Industry Minister Samarn Pummakanchana.
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- About one in three music compact discs (CDs) sold
here in the first six months of this year was pirated, making for
the highest level of piracy in Singapore in recent years, the
Straits Times reported today, citing findings from the
International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI).
</P>
<P>
The findings showed that pirated CD sales now have increased to
about 30 percent of the market, or about 13.8 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's Economic Ministry has drafted a framework
for enterprises reform in a bid to speed up the nation's sluggish
economic growth, the Interfax news agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the framework, enterprises should first make efforts to
attract investors both from home and abroad, protect the interests
of all shareholders, and divide clearly the responsibilities
between the owners and the managements.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The United Nations (UN) will determine the
quantity of oil to be imported by India from Iraq under a barter
deal to be supervised by the world body, the Times of India
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the progress on the proposed crude import, Indian
Petroleum Secretary Vijay Kelkar said, "The United Nations will
fix the quantity of oil to be imported by India according to a
formula worked out by it."
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- A ferry carrying twice its maximum passenger load
sank Sunday morning on the waters in Pangkep district, Indonesia's
South Sulawesi Province, killing at least 13 people.
</P>
<P>
Eleven other passengers were injured, including five in
critical conditions, while scores of others went missing, reports
reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission has recently decided to
send a formal warning letter to the Bonn government over subsidies
paid out to a number of German coal mining companies.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s executive body asked the German
authorities in the letter either to justify the aid payments,
which appear to be having a distortive effect on the EU market,
especially for anthracite, or to explain how they intend to remedy
the situation.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Turkey has recently lashed out at the European
Commission's decision to prepare for EU membership for five
Central and Eastern European countries and Cyprus but not to
include Turkey on the list of potential members.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, described the decision by
the EU's executive body as negative and held out hope that the EU
Council of Ministers would "correct" the decision.
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- The Myanmar authorities seized a total of 540.64
kilograms of narcotics in the country in June, the official daily
The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The seizure, which included 19.13 kilograms of heroin and
294.73 kilograms of different kinds of opium, was made by the army
 units, police force and customs. The Myanmar authorities took
action against 481 people in 360 drug-related cases in the month,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
