<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Situation Getting Worse in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- AIDS has taken its greatest toll
of victims in sub-Saharan Africa and Kenya has not escaped the
epidemic, according to a special report issued here today by East
African Standard.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Aids situation in Kenya had been
getting worse since the first identified case in 1984, with the
percentage of HIV positive people in the country's population
increasing from 3.5 percent in 1990 to 7.5 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that by the year 2000, 10 percent of 28
million of Kenya's population will be infected by the virus.
</P>
<P>
The true number of people suffering from Aids can only be
estimated but it is believed that more than 200,000 Kenyans have
developed full-blown AIDS.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that in 1996, 111 Kenyans died of the disease
every day and more than 65,500 cases of AIDS had been reported to
the Ministry of Health since 1984.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the virus is enormous socially, economically and
demographically, consequently the HIV/AIDS crisis in the east
African country is far more than a health issue.
</P>
<P>
The special report said that the future development of the
country's economy was directly under threat as a result of the
spread of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Studies already suggest that an average of 4 percent of
profits are being lost by companies as more than one in seven of
Nairobi's workforce is presently HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that by the year 2000, Kenya's GDP will be
almost 15 percent less than it could have been without the HIV
virus.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the spread of HIV/AIDS, the public health
sector will bear an enormous burden with as much as 50 percent of
all public health expenditure spending on AIDS patients by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, 15 percent of hospital beds were occupied by AIDS
patients whereas the rate is currently estimated at 60 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0132 </DOCNO>
