<HEADLINE> Thailand Mulls Over Establishing Muslim Food Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Industry Ministry of Thailand
is studying the idea of establishing a Muslim food production
complex to cater to the world's 1.5 billion Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The complex, to be located in southern Thailand which has a
large Muslim community and is near to Muslims-dominated Malaysia,
is part of the ministry's 'food for the world' vision, according
to Deputy Industry Minister Samarn Pummakanchana.
</P>
<P>
An integrated production center will be set up to engage in
processes from farming to hygiene and systematic production of
Muslim food, local newspaper the Nation today quotes him as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Samarn sees great potential for Thailand to export Muslim food,
especially to India and Indonesia, because of its geographical
advantage.
</P>
<P>
Maximum incentives are to be provided to investors in the
complex, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month Industry Minister Korn Dabbaransi approved
the forming of a committee to study the feasibility of the
complex.  
</P>
