<HEADLINE> Chinese Progress in Missile Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's Outlook Magazine
published an article today of senior officers of the Second Artillery
Force (SAF) of China's People's Liberation Army (PLA) discussing the
growth and major achievements of China's guided missile force over
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The SAF was founded on July 1, 1966 with the approval of the
late Chairman Mao Zedong and Premier Zhou Enlai, and entered a new
period of development in the 1990s. It has developed a
comprehensive training system for simulated missile launches and
exercises by missile troops, improved equipment, and operations
suited to modern warfare, said Yang Guoliang, commander of the SAF.
</P>
<P>
Its logistics departments have helped it keep abreast of arms
and equipment used in modern warfare, engineering, and military
research.
</P>
<P>
It has a strong contingent of military researchers, and
more than 70 percent of the SAF officers are college graduates.
</P>
<P>
The exercises in the East Sea and South China Sea in 1995 and 1996
were a comprehensive test of SAF's combat readiness, Yang noted.
</P>
<P>
"We have developed a limited number of strategic nuclear arms
for the sake of breaking the nuclear monopoly, opposing nuclear
blackmail, containing a possible nuclear attack, and creating a
peaceful environment for China's construction," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, the Chinese people and the officers and men
of China's missile force welcome nuclear disarmament and are
opposed to the nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear disarmament by the nuclear powers, he pointed out, was
merely a reduction in the number of out-moded models, while the
competition in developing a new generation of nuclear arms
continues.
</P>
<P>
The missile force will follow a road to a bright new world
under the leadership by the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee and the Central Military Commission headed by Jiang
Zemin, he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One in Three CDs Sold in Singapore Believed to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- About one in three music compact
discs (CDs) sold here in the first six months of this year was
pirated, making for the highest level of piracy in Singapore in
recent years, the Straits Times reported today, citing findings
from the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry
(IFPI).
</P>
<P>
The findings showed that pirated CD sales now have increased to
about 30 percent of the market, or about 13.8 million US dollars,
from 12 percent of the market, or about 4.6 million US dollars,
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Singapore's music industry is worth more than 69
million US dollars a year in retail sales of CDs and cassettes,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The IFPI, which represents the music industry worldwide, also
found that local pirates were not only copying but also producing
and releasing their own CD albums before the legitimate copyright
owners could do.
</P>
<P>
It said that there are four or five well-organized networks
involved in CD piracy in Singapore, and it believed that three or
four of the eight CD manufacturing plants here are involved in
producing pirated CDs.
</P>
<P>
Pirated CDs are sold through more than 100 make-shift stalls
set up outside housing estate shops, trade fairs, and in night and
weekend markets. They are also sold door-to-door in housing
estates, offices, factories, and at local food centers.
</P>
<P>
Last week, one of the biggest syndicates, believed to have
controlled half of the market, was put out of action in a police
raid, in which about 80,000 CDs, worth nearly 65 million US
dollars in retail value, were seized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
