<HEADLINE> Sprinters Offer Canada little Hope of World Glory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Canada's national track and field
championships ended Sunday, showing little signs of glory at next
month's World Championships.
</P>
<P>
None of the competitors reached the world standards for their
events on the three-day meet.
</P>
<P>
Breaking the mold Sunday were Robert Esmie in the men's 200m in
20.78 seconds and Philomenia Marsh in the women's 200m in 23.56.
</P>
<P>
Running against headwinds, Esmie clocked just 0.67 seconds more
than the Canadian national record in his discipline.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 200m, Marsh met no competition as she easily run
to her top honour.
</P>
<P>
The biggest gold hope for Canada in Athens, nevertheless, is
pinned on Donovan Bailey.
</P>
<P>
Although dissatisfied with his performance on Saturday with a
10.03-second victory in the 100m, Bailey gave the home crowds the
only hope that Canada might have a place among the major athletic
nations of the world.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the men's 4x100 meters relay that Canada won in the
Atlanta Olympics, the country's another expectation of a credible
performance comes in the women's 1,500m as Leah Pells clocked in 4
minutes 07.26 seconds, followed by Robyn Meagher in 4:07.68.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian team for the World Championships is expected to be
announced on July 21st. 
</P>
