<HEADLINE> Pakistan Continues Shuttle Diplomacy in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Pakistani diplomat has
left today for Kandahar, a major city in southern Afghanistan, to
carry forward Pakistan's shuttle diplomacy for peace in
Afghanistan, a Foreign Office official said.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Iftikhar Murshed, additional foreign secretary, to
Kandahar, stronghold of Afghan Islamic Taliban militia, takes
place a few days after Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Allaudin
Broujerdi's visit to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Tehran and Islamabad agreed to use their
influence to induce the Taliban and the rival northern alliance to
sit together for a peaceful settlement to the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Murshed held talks with the leadership
of the northern alliance in Mazar-e-Sharif during which all
expressed willingness to enter into political dialogue for moving
towards the realization of peace in the strife-seized country.
</P>
<P>
The northern alliance, based in Mazar-e-Sharif, has put forward
the idea of setting up a joint political commission for a
broad-based government in Afghanistan while the Taliban called for
the unconditional release of their senior officials including
foreign minister Mulla Muhammad Ghous as a confidence-building
measure for talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
