<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Hold Trade Fair in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Eleven Sri Lankan companies will
participate in a three-day trade and industrial fair in Yokohama,
Japan, this week organized by the National Chamber of Industries
in collaboration with the Japanese Yokohama Industrial
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the fair scheduled for July 22-24 is to
exhibit to potential buyers the high-quality exportable products
manufactured by Sri Lanka for a rapid expansion of trade to Japan,
according to Trade Ministry sources here today.
</P>
<P>
Among the items on display are leather goods, rubber goods,
fiber goods, tea, textiles, gems and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
The fair is expected to attract potential investors by
informing them of the advantages of investing in Sri Lanka, the
sources noted.
</P>
<P>
The trade fair was decided upon following the changing
attitudes of Japanese investors favorably towards Sri Lanka,
particularly in areas where the Sri Lankan participants are
engaged in, they added.
</P>
<P>
The value of Sri Lanka's imports from Japan in 1996 was 465.8
million U.S. dollars while Sri Lanka's exports to Japan stood at
238.5 million U.S. dollars, leaving the trade balance largely in
favor of Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
