<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Suffers Heavy Losses in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The severe flooding this summer,
preceded by the bitter cold last winter, is sure to bring down
Poland's agricultural produce this year, experts have said.
</P>
<P>
The traditionally farming nation in East Europe is expected to
lose about 1 million metric tons of grains in the year, experts
were quoted as saying by latest newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the output of rapeseed, which is an essential raw
material for the country's production of cooking oil, may be down
to the historic low due to an expected loss of 100,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The past cold winter killed 450,000 hectares of crops, and
recent floodings inundated 8,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate Poland will harvest 23.8-24.3 million tons of
grains this year, or about 1 million tons less than last year,
making it the second year in a row for lower grain output.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Poland lost 900,000 tons of grains.
</P>
<P>
In rapeseed production, half of the rape died early this year
in the coldness hitting the provinces of Opole, Walbrzych and
Wroclaw, which produce most of the country's rapeseed.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated harvest of 300,000 tons of rapeseed this
year, Poland is likely to import 600,000 tons to meet the domestic
demands for cooking oil, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Currency of Taka Devalued Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi currency of taka has
been devalued by 45 poisha against the U.S. dollar with effect
from today, according to local banking sources.
</P>
<P>
With the fresh devaluation, the fourth in this calendar year,
the Bangladesh Bank's buying rate for one dollar from the banks is
now 44 taka instead of the earlier rate 43.55. The selling rate is
now 44.20 instead of 43.75 taka earlier.
</P>
<P>
An official of the central bank said that the dollar was going
strong in the last few weeks which demanded downward adjustment of
the taka.
</P>
<P>
He also said exports which had been declining in recent months
also needed a boost, calling for a devaluation.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the market had been expecting a devaluation in the
wake of falling foreign exchange reserve, current account deficit
and fall in exports, said a market analyst.  
</P>
</TEXT>
