<HEADLINE> Thai Tapioca Exports to EU to Drop Due to Pig Epidemic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Exports of Thai tapioca to the
European Union (EU) this year will be lower than last year as a
result of an epidemic which has killed more than five million pigs
in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is the largest EU tapioca pellet importer from
Thailand. Tapioca is imported for animal feed raw material.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's tapioca exports to the EU this year will fall short
of the 3.5 million ton target, compared to 4 million tons last
year, according to Boonchai Srichaiyongphanich, president of the
Thai Tapioca Trade Association.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the depreciation of the German currency has
automatically driven up the price of tapioca from Thailand, making
it more expensive than other cereals sold in the EU. Users have
shifted to buy cheaper raw materials such as maize and have
reduced purchases of the Thai product.
</P>
<P>
The lower demand for tapioca will add to the overall decline in
Thailand's exports for the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Boonchai said tapioca exports to the EU in the near future will
not recover if the government does not help cassava planters to
reduce production costs and increase productivity, adding that
export policy should be streamlined to reduce operating costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
