<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants to See Strong, Resilient ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi here today called for a new and better
Southeast Asia by the year 2020 that is strong and resilient in
all fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"We must aim for a new and better Southeast Asia by the year
2020. It must be a Southeast Asia that is strong and resilient in
all the political, economic, social and security fundamentals. It
must be a Southeast Asia that has human welfare in all its
comprehensiveness at the heart of its concerns. It must be a
Southeast Asia that is able to share pride of place and work in
mutual respect and cooperation with all the major centers of power
in the world," he said when opening the Second ASEAN Congress
here.
</P>
<P>
The three-day congress is organized by the Institute of
Strategic and International Studies (ISIS) as part of ASEAN's 30th
anniversary which falls on August 8 this year.
</P>
<P>
Over 150 government officials and experts from ASEAN members --
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam -- and from Laos and Cambodia, are participating in
the congress.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address, Abdullah, who is also the ASEAN
Standing Committee Chairman, outlined five achievements of ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) during its 30 years'
existence and five challenges in the immediate years ahead.
</P>
<P>
Among the achievements, he said the most important is the
restoration and enhancement of mutual understanding, confidence
and trust among the member-states to replace the climate of
suspicion and mistrust that prevailed among them.
</P>
<P>
The institution of norms of acceptable conduct and behavior
among its members as enshrined in the various ASEAN instruments is
ASEAN's another great achievement.
</P>
<P>
He counted ASEAN's ability to keep its region out of major
power conflict as another of its significant achievement.
</P>
<P>
The fourth accomplishment of ASEAN, he said, would be the
emphasis on comprehensive cooperation, in particular economic and
functional cooperation, as the bedrock of ASEAN collaboration.
</P>
<P>
He said the fifth achievement would be ASEAN's emergence as a
regional grouping of significant political consequence in the
larger international arena.
</P>
<P>
On challenges, Abdullah said the first and for the moment the
most urgent would be to realize the vision of all of Southeast
Asia united in common purpose under ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said one of the challenges ahead of ASEAN would be the
challenge of maintaining cohesion and preserving consensus as the
ASEAN membership is nearly doubled in the short span of just two
or three years.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's continued viability, empowerment and standing in the
international arena will also be very much a function of how
economically vibrant and healthy it continues to be as it expands.
Poor countries and groupings of the poor are neither heard nor
heeded. ASEAN's third challenge resides here, he said.
</P>
<P>
A fourth challenge, he said, would be the challenge of
"fostering a truly stable and peaceful Southeast Asia".
</P>
<P>
And he considered the fifth challenge as the most daunting yet
the most rewarding, that is, "the challenge of raising the quality
of our lives, materially as well as spiritually".
</P>
<P>
Abdullah called on all ASEAN members to strengthen peace and
stability within their borders, saying "this peace and stability
cannot be of the brittle variety enforced by the power of the
gun."
</P>
<P>
It must be a peace and stability that is sustainable and
durable, built on good governance, satisfaction of the people's
legitimate needs and fulfillment of their legitimate aspiration,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We look to a Southeast Asia that has resolved all
territorial disputes and all border politics by the year 2020."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
