<HEADLINE> Thailand's Sugar Exports to Fall for Lack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's sugar exports in the
1997/1998 production year are expected to decrease for lack of
rain.
</P>
<P>
The country's sugar exports for 1997/1998 would be reduced to
3.5 million tons, from 4.2 million tons of this year (1996/ 1997).
In the previous year, the exports were 4.4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Prolonged dry season will reduce Thailand's sugar output in
1997/1998 to between 4.7 and 4.9 million tons, against the 5.8
million ton target.
</P>
<P>
Of all the sugarcane plantations, only 15 percent are located
in irrigated areas, according to a state-run sugar company
official.
</P>
<P>
However, if there is sufficient rain in August and September,
Thailand can still maintain its position as the world's fourth
largest sugar exporter, after Brazil, the European union and
Australia, according to Surat Abhikleophan, marketing chief of the
Thai Cane and Sugar Corp.  
</P>
</TEXT>
