<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Happy with Hefty Rise in Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China's railway industry has
achieved a noteworthy growth in profit since a national
operational scheme to raise train speed was launched in April,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that the growth was accompanied by a 6.2 percent
decrease in passenger flow in the past three months. During the
same period, the number of passenger trains decreased by 120
pairs, or 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Since April 1, train speed on three major lines -
Beijing-Guangzhou, Beijing-Shanghai and Beijing-Harbin - has been
increased to maximum of 140 kilometers per hour, and trains on
other lines to a maximum of 120 kilometers per hour, both up from
about 100 kilometers per hour. Ticket prices remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-four direct express trains and "overnight trains" have
been opened, linking rail hubs within 1,000-1,500 kilometers of
one another, and many low-speed and short-distance trains have
been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
In the past three months, railway transport has been on a
steady rise. A sharp rise in passengers on direct express trains
and "overnight trains" is partly responsible for the growth in
profits.
</P>
<P>
The opening of 703 shuttle cargo trains, which had not existed
in China before, has also been highly welcomed, the paper says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
