<HEADLINE> Michael Chang Wins Washington Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Top-seeded American Michael
Chang on Sunday rallied past second seed Peter Korda of the Czech
Republic 5-7, 6-2, 6-1 to win his second straight Washington
Classic championship.
</P>
<P>
Chang captured his ATP Tour-leading fifth singles title of the
season, breaking a tie with world No. 1 Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
Chang won 90,000 U.S. dollars as he boosted his 1997 record to
41-10, including a remarkable 28-3 record on the hard surface.
</P>
<P>
Chang, 25, improved to 6-2 lifetime against Korda, including
4-0 on hardcourts. He has won 31 career ATP Tour titles, 19 of
them on hardcourts.
</P>
<P>
Korda, 29, ranked 21st in the world, was seeking his second
career Washington Classic title after his victory in 1992.
</P>
<P>
It also marked his second final of the year after losing to
Yevgeny Kafelnikov at last month's Gerry Weber Open in Halle,
Germany. 
</P>
