<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronics Industry Rises in Output, Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China's electronics industry
scored a 20.9 percent increase in production during the first six
months of this year, with its value-added output hitting a record
3.2 billion US dollars, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes Liu Jianfeng, vice-minister of Electronics
Industry as saying that industry profits also racked up a parallel
development, totalling 536 million US dollars during January-June,
up 21.9 percent on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Liu noted strong market demand has sparked electronics
factories to gear up production. He warned duplication of the same
electronic projects has also become rampant nationwide, especially
in TV and video compact disc (VCD) manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
In the coming months the ministry will use administrative
means to rein in the development of new projects in an attempt to
avoid "blind expansion" of the electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry plans to strengthen its manufacturing technology
appraisal for new projects. It will also strictly control issuing
production licences to factories which apply for electronics
production.
</P>
<P>
Factories were urged to seek survival through branching into
international markets, and stop suicide behavior as slashing their
retail prices, the paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
