<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ankara Upset at Being Left Out of EU Expansion Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has recently lashed out at
the European Commission's decision to prepare for EU membership
for five Central and Eastern European countries and Cyprus but not
to include Turkey on the list of potential members, it was learned
here today.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish authorities reportedly condemned Cyprus's inclusion
on the first wave list, stressing that the island state's
membership before a solution to the partition issue is found "out
of the question."
</P>
<P>
Bulent Ecevit, Turkey's deputy prime minister, even went so far
as to threaten that should this come to pass, Turkey would embark
on a process of "partial integration" with the Turkish-speaking
northern part of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In the Agenda 2000 document on future EU enlargements, the
Commission confined itself to pointing out that Turkey is still
eligible as a candidate but its current political situation allows
no plans for the time being to alter the negative opinion the
Commission gave on its 1989 bid for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, described the decision by
the EU's executive body as negative and held out hope that the EU
Council of Ministers would "correct" the decision.
</P>
<P>
He said that EU membership would continue to be a high-priority
concern for Turkey, according to a spokesman for the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
However, in the section on Turkey in its Agenda 2000 document,
the Commission says that the start up of the EU-Turkey Customs
Union, on December 31 of 1995, was a "major step forward in
relations between the two sides."
</P>
<P>
Turkey is advised by the Commission to improve its tax
collection system, restructure and privatize public companies,
reform its social security system and rethink its public
expenditure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Marketing of Milk Test Kit Containing GMOS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
recently given the go-ahead for a Finnish company to market
throughout the EU a test kit containing a genetically-modified
micro-organism, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The test kit, which was notified by dairy group Valio Oy, will
allow rapid detection of antibiotic residues in milk.
</P>
<P>
The labels on each test kit will clearly indicate that they
contain a genetically-modified organism, streptococcus
thermophilus T102.
</P>
<P>
The Commission's decision follows a favorable opinion by
qualified majority from the Regulatory Committee set up under an
EU directive on deliberate release into the environment of
genetically-modified organisms.
</P>
<P>
The marketing authorization for the test kit to be issued by
the relevant Finnish regulatory body will allow the product to be
used in dairy laboratories and milk-collecting vehicles in order
to detect any antibiotic residues in milk as quickly as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Nations Slash Australia Over Secret Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- South Pacific nations criticized
Australia for a scathing report about them, the Solomon Islands'
government said today.
</P>
<P>
The Solomons received some of the worst criticism in the
report.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the Solomons is facing economic collapse and
that one senior political figure there had a reputation for
corrupt dealings and was known in local business circles as "Mr
Ten Per Cent".
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Solomons Prime Minister Solomon Mamaloni said
while some of the criticisms may be valid, Australia should have
addressed them through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
"They should say 'look, we know things aren't going well. It
doesn't look good, can we help'," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The confidential report was prepared jointly by Australia's
Treasury and the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade as a
briefing for Treasurer Peter Costello for a summit of economic
ministers from the 16-member South Pacific Forum a week ago in
Cairns, North Queensland of Australia.
</P>
<P>
The document was left on a table in a public area at the
meeting, where it was obtained by the Reuters news agency.
</P>
<P>
The report also severely criticized New Zealand, Nauru and Cook
Islands.
</P>
<P>
Nauruan President Kinza Clodumar said on Saturday that he
regretted that Australian ministers were being "so badly and
inaccurately advised by their officials".
</P>
<P>
Cook Islands' Prime Minister Geoffrey Henry, dismissed as vain
and boastful in the briefing paper, said that it was unfair and
untrue to claim his country as being mismanaged.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Deputy Prime Minister Winston Peters, who was
described by the paper as an opportunist, has downplayed the report
as merely the opinion of an ignorant bureaucrat.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer has moved quickly
into damage control. In a television appearance on Saturday night,
Downer said that the report "did not represent government policy".
</P>
<P>
Australia's Acting Opposition Leader Gareth Evans has asked
Australia to apologize for the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
