<HEADLINE> Guo'an Sets Scoring Record of New China Soccer League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Guo'an recovered from a
1-5 defeat in the last round to set a scoring record of the
four-year China soccer league as it beat Shanghai Shenhua 9-1 at
home on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, who lost to Dalian Wada 1-5 last Sunday, dominated the
match, thanks to its three foreigners who scored eight of nine
goals for Guo'an.
</P>
<P>
The home players built a 5-1 lead in the first half but never
relaxed their holds before the refree's whistle was blown.
</P>
<P>
"It was unexpected scoring tonight," said Jin Zhiyang, head
coach of Beijing. "It was the first time for any team to score so
many since the new home-away format league founded four years
ago. Maybe it's also the last time for scoring so many."
</P>
<P>
The win promoted Beijing from fourth spot to second in the team
standings at a 4-4-2 record after the ten rounds.
</P>
<P>
Dalian, defending champion who has led the standings since the
beginning of this season, kept its record without loss though it
was tied by much lower August First 2-2 -- one of four tying
matches on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Wada now tops others with 8-2-0, while August First was 11th
with a poor 1-5-4 mark.
</P>
<P>
In day's only other win-loss match, Guangdong Hongyuan edged
Tianjin Samsung 2-1. Both scored in the first half.
</P>
<P>
In three other tying actions, Yanbian Aodong drew Guangzhou
Apollo 0-0, Jinan Taishan evened Vanguard Huandao 2-2, Sichuan
Quanxing tied Qingdao Hainiu 1-1.
</P>
<P>
Quanxing, 3-6-1, and Shenhua, 3-5-2, now stands third and
fourth respectively in the league. 
</P>
</TEXT>
