<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Adjourns Libel Case Against Mubarak's Sons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 20 (Xinhua) -- A court in the Egyptian capital of
Cairo today agreed to adjourn until Sunday the hearings into a
libel suit filed by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's sons
against a Saudi magazine.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the request of the defense attorneys,
the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Three Egyptians and three Saudis, including the magazine
owner, were charged on July 12 with the publication of a
slanderous story about the two plaintiffs, Alaa and Gamal Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The six face sentences of a maximum of three years in prison
each, and a fine for "defamation and attacking (Mubarak) family
honor."
</P>
<P>
The defendants had admitted wrongdoings and said they only
meant to promote the nascent magazine.
</P>
<P>
Ashraq Al Awsat daily, part of the Saudi publishing group of
the same name, advertised on May 27 for its sister weekly Al
Jadida containing an article implicating Mubarak's sons in
illegal business dealings.
</P>
<P>
Only Sayed Abdel-Atti, author of the article, lives in Egypt
while the others are in London, Britain, and Saudi Arabia and
will be tried in absentia, prosecution sources said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's sons sued the London-based daily for publishing
"lying articles and allegations about transactions, commissions
and illusionary monopolies with a premeditated aim of inflicting
severe harm and slander" on Egypt's first family.
</P>
<P>
The advertised article never appeared, and two of the weekly's
editors were sacked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
