<HEADLINE> Egypt Raises Recruit Salaries by 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
supreme commander of the armed forces, has issued an order to
increase the salaries of recruits by 15 percent as of July 1, the
Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is the seventh time Mubarak issued an order to raise the
salaries of recruits.
</P>
<P>
The MENA, when announcing the news, said the Supreme Commander
of the Armed Forces is "keen to provide a decent life for the
fighting soldier during the period of his compulsory service in
the armed forces."
</P>
<P>
"It also reflects the interest of the supreme commander in the
social state and services provided for recruits and their
families," it said.
</P>
<P>
A combined system of voluntary and compulsory military services
is applied in Egypt, a country boasting 500,000-strong armed
forces. Compulsory servicemen on a three-year stint get paid
300-450 Egyptian pounds (88.2-132.4 U.S. dollars) currently per
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
