<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Minerals Output Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe recorded a decline in its
output levels of most base minerals from major mines during the
first quarter of this year compared to the corresponding period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Finhold's Economic Review today attributed the decline to slow
recovery in commodity prices on international markets as a result
of the over-supply, accompanied by depressed demand.
</P>
<P>
The minerals are gold, coal, chrome-ore, low-carbon
ferrochrome, high-carbon ferrochrome and ferrosilicon.
</P>
<P>
The continued increase in production costs also resulted in
gradual scaling down of operations at some small, high cost and
low output mines, with some groups selling off the loss-making
ones and concentrating on large mines, Finhold said.
</P>
<P>
Gold output from major mines continued to decline during the
first five months of this year, recording a total of 9,812
kilograms valued at 111 million U.S. Dollars compared to 114
million Dollars during the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Coal output fell by 8.6 percent to 1.2 million tons in the
first quarter of this year, copper declined 23.8 percent, chrome
dropped slightly by 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, growth was registered in the production of nickel,
asbestos and iron-ore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report on S. Leone Soldiers Surrendering to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The military junta of Sierra
Leone today denied that 485 soldiers and rebel RUF fighters have
surrendered to ECOMOG bases in the capital as reported by a
newspaper "Tablet" here.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the soldiers gave themselves up
after last weekend's clashes in Jui, 17 miles east of the capital
between Sierra Leone's soldiers and Nigerian troops.
</P>
<P>
The junta's statement broadcast over the state radio said,
"the entire armed forces and the Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
continue to demonstrate their loyalty to the (military)
government."
</P>
<P>
It described the newspaper's claim as "a blatant act of
propaganda and the work of unpatriotic persons parading as
journalists to create panic and fear in the minds of the people".
</P>
<P>
The statement observed that the newspaper "is unregistered and
operating contrary to the rules and regulation governing
newspaper registration" in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a statement broadcast over a clandestine
pro-democracy radio said today that "some patriotic rebel
fighters and Sierra Leone soldiers are being prevented from
surrendering to ECOMOG bases by hard-core junta and RUF members."
</P>
<P>
Ousted President Tejan Kabbah said last week over the same
radio that soldiers should defect to the ECOMOG bases if they
don't want to be branded as mutineers.
</P>
<P>
According to the clandestine radio, "soldiers who wanted to
defect are threatened with death and told they will be killed by
ECOMOG troops if they give themselves up to the ECOMOG." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-20 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Officials Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy met here today with senior Palestinian negotiator Nabil
Shaath to discuss confidence-building measures to narrow the
differences between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour meeting was held under the auspices of the
European Union (EU) peace envoy Miguel Angel Moratinos, who has
been working hard to break the deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli's accusation of Palestinian police's involvement in
anti-Israeli extremism dominated today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday, Israeli security forces arrested three Palestinian
policemen, who were charged with attempting to carry out a
shooting attack against a Jewish settlement near the West Bank
city of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Levy presented Israel's evidence on the alleged Palestinian
police's involvement in the attempted shooting, and demanded the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to take actions instead of
words to uproot Palestinian militant activities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Levy said Israel
would be ready to reciprocate by advancing the peace process on
the following proposals: implementing the peace agreements by the
PNA by undertaking to prevent violence, incitement and extremism
against Israel; removing factors which undermine the Israel's
security such as the latest incident of police involvement; and
proceeding towards the final-status talks and even perhaps
speeding up the process.
</P>
<P>
Levy added he was pleased with the response from Shaath, who
promised that the PNA would take actions to prevent militant
actions.
</P>
<P>
But Shaath pointed out that the evidence was not conclusive
in Israel's allegation about Palestinian police's involvement in
anti-Israeli moves. He said no pretext should be used to derail
the efforts by both sides to break the peace impasse and create
confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the PNA wanted to move ahead the final-status
talks, but it also wanted the Israeli government to make
concessions on settlement activities and refrain from taking
unilateral steps.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian negotiator added that, under the Egyptian
initiative, the two sides were working closely to try to create
mutual confidence-building measures, such as opening safe
passages between the West Bank and Gaza Strip, releasing
Palestinian detainees, and continuing the building of a Gaza
airport and seaport.
</P>
<P>
"These are measures that we can hopefully do (for) the expected
security coordination and (that we) attempt to break the impasse
(so) that we can go back to the main problems that have created
this crisis," Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos voiced optimism about the prospect of advancing the
peace process as the two sides began narrowing their differences
on the issues of security cooperation, improving Palestinian
economy and other confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was the result of Moratinos' intensive
efforts to arrange a meeting between Levy and PNA President
Yasser Arafat Tuesday in Brussels of Belgium during the EU
foreign ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
Levy is already scheduled to attend the gathering, where
Arafat has yet announced his intention to make the trip. If Levy
and Arafat meet, this will be their second meeting sponsored by
the EU since the first one in Malta on April 15 at the
European-Mediterranean Foreign Ministers' Conference.
</P>
<P>
Levy said he would be happy to meet Arafat if the latter
decided to go. He also appealed to the Arab world to cease what
he called "a diplomatic war" against Israel and to change the
climate into one of peace among the Arab public.
</P>
<P>
The Levy-Shaath meeting was held amid rumors that the United
States intended to launch a new round of diplomatic offensive to
break the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
