<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Government Vows to Wipe out Man-eating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The government of Tanzania
today vowed to continue fighting hand in hand with Mkuranga
district residents in Coast region in an effort to wipe out
man-eating lions to save the people from further killings.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism Zakia Meghji told
Mkuranga residents at separate meetings with Mbezi and Mkuranga
villagers when she went to console relatives of the deceased
killed by the beasts, that the government has sent enough
ammunition and rangers to combat the lions.
</P>
<P>
She thanked the leaders in the community for sending scouts to
take part in the operation. Six scouts armed with guns and
powerful light have camped at Mbezi village to help search for
the beasts, she added.
</P>
<P>
The man-eater lions have claimed 17 lives of people, injured
11, and villagers have managed to kill 18 lions since February
this year.
</P>
<P>
The minister pledged government assistance of 50,000 Tanzania
Shillings (about 83 U.S. Dollars) to relatives of the deceased on
every member of the family killed, and the money would be
channeled through Mkuranga district commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Zakia Meghji also expressed condolences sent to them by
President Benjamin Mkapa and Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye to
the family members who had their relatives eaten by the beasts.
</P>
<P>
According to a report, a score of lions invaded Mkuranga
districts at the end of last year from Seleous Game Reserve in
search of water and have settled down in the district. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
