<HEADLINE> Arafat Meets With Jordanian Prime Minister In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat and Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali today
expressed their strong desire to strengthen the Palestine-Jordan
ties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after their talks in the West
Bank city of Ramallah, the two leaders said that their
discussions focused primarily on further developing economic
cooperation between the two sides, according to a report of JMCC,
a Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came at a time when relations between Jordan and
Israel remain further cooled off. The signing of a memorandum of
understanding on the joint Jordanian-Israeli airport project at
Aqaba, which was scheduled for today, has been delayed, reported
the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Transport Minister, Yitzhak Levy, was due to have
met with his Jordanian counterpart to sign the document in
the Red Sea port city today.
</P>
<P>
Instead, an Israeli civil aviation delegation will hold
further talks with the Jordanians in Aqaba Tuesday. The dispute
reportedly rests primarily with security-related issues.
</P>
<P>
It appears that Israel is far from being happy over the
Jordanian handling of the Naharayim case. A military court
sentenced the Jordanian soldier who killed seven Israeli girls to
life in prison, short of a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
The soldier, Ahmed Daqamsa, 26, was charged with the
premeditated murder of the girls, who were shot to death during an
outing in Naharayim on the Jordan River. 
</P>
