<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Inkatha Resolves to Replace Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Inkatha Freedom Party
(IFP), the biggest black Opposition party in South Africa, has
claimed it is destined to lead the struggle for economic
prosperity and emancipation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The claim was made at an IFP's annual general conference,
which ended in Ulundi, Kwazulu Natal Province, today after three
days of deliberation, which saw the election of Zakhele Khumalo
as the party's new general secretary.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the IFP leaders said South Africa needs a
strong, principled and honest government which plans to move
speedily toward prosperity. Only the IFP's contribution could
provide this, it claimed.
</P>
<P>
The conference said South Africa has achieved political
freedom but not true liberation and democracy, which would be
scored when the majority enjoy a dignified life free from need
and want.
</P>
<P>
"The ruling party (African National Congress) is paralyzed by
indecision, ambivalence and lack of vision and is jeopardizing
the goals of the struggle.
</P>
<P>
"Only the IFP, with its political, economic and social vision
of federalism, pluralism, market economy and family values, is
destined to lead the struggle for economic prosperity and
emancipation," the party noted.
</P>
<P>
Sources closed to the meeting said the IFP leaders were trying
to focus on restructuring the party to prepare for the 1999
general elections.
</P>
<P>
In addition to political preparation, the sources said, the
IFP was making efforts to raise money for the participation of
the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
Joe Matthews, Deputy Safety and Security Minister and IFP
National Council member, said the IFP would need almost 100
million Rand (22 million U.S. Dollars) to fund its election
campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
