<HEADLINE> Cyprus Marks 23rd Anniversary of Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- With flags hoisted at half-mast, a
memorial service was held here today to mark the 23rd anniversary
of the Turkish occupation of part of Cyprus since 1974.
</P>
<P>
The memorial service was led this morning by the Primate of
the Church of Cyprus Archbishop Chrysostomos in memory of all who
lost their lives during the invasion.
</P>
<P>
The service was attended by Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides,
other government officials, and political party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after the memorial service, Clerides
said that today is a day of remembrance of those who gave their
lives for the freedom of the country.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops landed on this eastern Mediterranean island on
July 20, 1974, and seized the northern third of the island
following a coup five days earlier, engineered by the military
junta ruling Greece in 1974.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that any solution to the Cyprus problem should not
allow repetition of what happened in the past.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the service, Cypriot Minister of Finance
Christodoulos Christodoulou stressed the need for unity among
Greek Cypriots and cooperation with the Greek government.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the people of Cyprus to look to the future
with optimism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, various activities were organized today to condemn
the Turkish invasion and continuing occupation of part of the
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
