<HEADLINE> Italian President Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar
Luigi Scalfaro ended his official visit to Saudi Arabia today,
during which he held talks with Saudi leaders on regional
issues as well as bilateral economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro, accompanied by a high-level delegation, arrived in
Saudi Arabia Saturday on a two-day state visit, the first by an
Italian president in 23 years, Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
During their talks in Jeddah, Saudi King Fahd Bin Abdul Aziz
and Scalfaro discussed means of boosting economic, trade and
investment cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Italian embassy sources in Saudi Arabia as
saying that the two countries have agreed to hold wide range
talks in the future on issues discussed by the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Italy signed last September a cooperation and
investment protection agreement which also bans dual taxation.
</P>
<P>
Trade exchanges between Saudi Arabia and Italy in 1995
amounted to 3.2 billion U.S. dollars with 747 million dollars in
Saudi favor, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also been linked by a security pact
since December 1995, which calls for joint cooperation in
combating organized crimes, drugs and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, Scalfaro and King Fahd
expressed fear that collapse of the peace process would threaten
the region's security, stability and peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro underlined his country and the European Union's
interest in reactivating the peace process, saying that
Israeli settlements in the occupied lands were illegal and
created an obstacle to the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro and King Fahd also discussed the situation in the
Gulf area, stressing the necessity of Iraq's implementation of
U.N. resolutions relevant to its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
They expressed content for the renewal of oil-for-food
agreement between Iraq and the U.N., which allows Iraq to export
2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to buy food
and medicines for the Iraqi people hit hard by U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
They also reiterated that lifting the sanctions on Iraq
depended on its compliance with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
