<HEADLINE> Former Turkish PM Rebuffs CIA Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Turkish Prime Minister Tansu
Ciller categorically rejected today the accusations that she had
been working as an agent for the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency
(CIA).
</P>
<P>
This came in a statement issued by her True Path Party (DYP),
which said that it was unreasonable and illogical attempting to
defame the reputation of Ciller, also current DYP chairman, adding
the accusations aimed to serve some politicians' personal
interests.
</P>
<P>
Workers' Party Chairman Dogu Perincek initially accused Ciller
of working for the CIA against Turkey, and then the general staff
of the Turkish Armed Forces ordered a probe into the alleged case
last week.
</P>
<P>
The DYP statement also criticized Turkey's media organizations
for helping fuel the accusations, saying they were taking a
revenge on Ciller, who served as Turkey's first woman prime
minister from 1993-96.
</P>
<P>
She was also deputy prime minister and foreign minister in the
coalition government of Necmettin Erbakan which resigned in June
18.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said that a deputy from the ruling
Motherland Party (ANAP) had earlier filed an spy case against
Ciller in a U.S. court in order to clarify what is termed as her
U.S. citizenship and assets issues in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
After the U.S. court, however, refused to accept and hear the
case, the ANAP deputy claimed that Washington was "protecting
Ciller."
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department Spokesman Nicolas Burns reportedly
denied earlier that the U.S. intelligence hired Ciller to work
against the national interests of Turkey, describing such
accusations as "ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
Since the resignation of Erbakan's government, there have been
rumors here that the new government led by Mesut Yilmaz will
launch a judicial offensive against the well-known woman
politician.
</P>
<P>
Ciller has long been accused of involvement in corruption
scandals, and her husband, a businessman, was said to have links
with mafia activities.
</P>
<P>
The military and opposition parties are greatly dissatisfied
with Ciller because her cooperation with the Welfare Party (RP)
led by Erbakan, who was vehmently attacked for the rapid growth
of fundamentalist tendency in Turkey during his nearly one-year
term of office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
