<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outcome of Liberian Polls Yet to Come out: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Liberian politicians and electoral
authorities today gave no hint of the outcome of the crucial
</P>
<P>
Rather than announcing the expected first results, most radio
stations in the capital Monrovia played religious music, while
many Monrovians prepared to attend church services, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The two front-running parties contesting the polls, the
National Patriotic Party of former warlord Charles Taylor and the
Unity Party of Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, preferred to remain
discreet when questioned about the probable outcome of the polls.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Electoral Commission (IECOM) said it would
deal firmly with anyone releasing results before its approval.
</P>
<P>
IECOM is not expected to announce the final results of the
polls contested by 13 parties before Wednesday, July 23.
</P>
<P>
The election on Saturday proceeded peacefully and orderly with
an exceptionally large turnout of voters, many of whom got up
before dawn to queue and cast their votes for the first time
since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Among Liberia's estimated 2.6 million people, more than
710,000 were registered as voters.
</P>
<P>
Hopes are high that the election will lead to final peace in
Liberia after seven years of civil war that has devastated the
country and killed over 150,000 people, displacing many more
people.
</P>
<P>
The hefty turnout showed Liberians' overwhelming yearning for
demoractic transition and peace.
</P>
<P>
"This is the day everybody has been waiting for," a report
quoted Archbishop Michael Francis as saying in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
IECOM officials began counting as soon as polls ended at
around 4 p.m. local time on Saturday in the presence of party
agents, international observers and soldiers of the west African
peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
If no presidential candidate wins more than 50 percent of
votes cast on Saturday#,a second round of voting will be held on
August 2, to decide who will be the last winner as president.
</P>
<P>
Liberia celebrates its 150th birthday on July 26. Freed
American slaves founded it as Africa's first modern republic.
</P>
<P>
The election will also produce a parliament of 90 members,
including 26 senators and 64 representatives, whose seats will be
allocated by proportional representation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
