<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sends Formal Warning to Bonn on Subsidies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
recently decided to send a formal warning letter to the Bonn
government over subsidies paid out to a number of German coal
mining companies, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s executive body asked the German
authorities in the letter either to justify the aid payments,
which appear to be having a distortive effect on the EU market,
especially for anthracite, or to explain how they intend to remedy
the situation.
</P>
<P>
This is reportedly the first stage of the state aid inquiry
procedures provided by EU legislation.
</P>
<P>
If no satisfactory response is forthcoming from Bonn, the next
step would be a formal statement of the perceived infringements
noted by the Commission -- known as a reasoned opinion, after
which the EU executive may decide to take legal action before the
European Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry was triggered by a complaint forwarded to the
Commission in early June by Celtic Energy, an anthracite producer
from the UK's South Wales valley, alleging that subsidized German
anthracite was being "dumped" on the UK market.
</P>
<P>
Two German mining enterprises -- Preussag Anthrazit and Sophia
Jacoba -- have managed to capture around 25 percent of the UK's
400,000-ton-per-annum market for high-energy coal.
</P>
<P>
Celtic management claims that its German rivals are conducting
an "aggressive" campaign, selling below true cost price with the
help of national aid grants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970721.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Restructuring Plan for Italian Airline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, has recently authorized a
revamped Italian government plan to pump 275,000 billion Lire
(some 1.85 billion U.S. dollars) in state aid into ailing airline
Alitalia.
</P>
<P>
The injection, which will be delivered in three separate
instalments to be released in tandem with the fulfilment of strict
conditions, is reportedly part of a restructuring program approved
by the EU commissioners in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The program calls for an overall 10 percent reduction in the
Italian flag carrier's operations and a freeze on the fleet size
and will additionally require sell-offs of some of the company's
non-core business.
</P>
<P>
The accompanying cost-cutting and rationalization exercise will
also lead to the loss of over 1,200 jobs over the period from 1996
to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Alitalia is Europe's fifth largest airline in terms of
passengers per kilometer, after British Airways, Lufthansa, Air
France and KLM.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the company -- which is 87 percent-owned by Italian
state industrial holding company IRI -- turned over 7,830,000
million Lire (about 5,200 million dollars) worth of business with
a workforce of 17,390 and a fleet of 157 aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
